<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Total plans FFr4bn capital increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOTAL, the French oil group, has concluded plans for a FFr4.07bn (Pounds
480m) capital increase with three new minority investors as the first step
towards creating a group of friendly shareholders to take long-term stakes
in the company.
Total is selling new shares representing 7 per cent of its equity to Cogema,
the state-controlled nuclear group, Societe Generale, the bank, and the
Lyonnaise des Eaux-Dumez industrial concern. Mr Serge Tchuruk, chairman,
said he hoped to engineer similar deals so that friendly investors
controlled 10 per cent to 12 per cent of Total.
The capital increase, involving Total taking reciprocal stakes in its new
investors and leaving it with FFr2.5bn of additional net cash, comes as
French companies prepare for the new government's privatisation programme.
Total, in which the government retains a 5 per cent direct stake and
indirectly owns 10 per cent of shares through state-controlled companies,
sees the formation of a group of friendly shareholders as a way of
stabilising its equity base.
The stock market reacted badly to the capital increase, which excludes
ordinary shareholders and assembles defensive shareholdings to defuse the
threat of changes in ownership. Total's shares fell 1.56 per cent to
FFr265.10.
Cogema has agreed to pay FFr2.5bn for a 4.3 per cent stake in Total and to
buy the latter's uranium interests for FFr1bn. Total plans to invest
FFr1.5bn in Cogema to acquire a 10 per cent holding. Societe Generale, a
long-standing adviser to Total, will take a 2 per cent stake in the oil
group in return for contributing FFr1bn to its shareholders' funds. Total
will buy 1 per cent of the bank for FFr500m. Lyonnaise will invest FFr500m
in Total, emerging with a 2 per cent stake. Total will then spend FFr500m to
take a 20 per cent holding in Ufiner-Cofreth, a Lyonnaise heating and energy
subsidiary.
Total said the transactions will help reduce net debt from FFr14.5bn to
FFr12bn and increase shareholders' funds from FFr46.8bn to FFr51bn. Gearing
will fall from 31 per cent to 24 per cent, helping it with plans to double
its oil and gas reserves by the end of the century.
Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
