<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Ciampi chooses a broad team: Italian ex-communists to work
with Christian Democrats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR CARLO Azeglio Ciampi last night broke the post-war mould of Italian
politics by including former communists and a member of the Green party in a
government that also has Christian Democrats in its ranks.
The 72-year-old premier-designate, who is also the governor of the Bank of
Italy, is the first non-parliamentarian to head a government this century.
He has spent two days trying to form a team to tackle electoral reform and
manage the economy.
His choice of a broadly-based team comes in response to the public's demand
for an era of clean politics after more than a year of damaging revelations
of corruption in the establishment.
For the first time a premier-designate has invoked article 92 of the
constitution which permits the formation of a government without direct
consultation with the party leaders. Until now all post-war governments have
been dictated by party leaders.
This coalition has been closely co-ordinated with President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro and is expected to last as long as it is necessary to draw up
legislation for electoral reform.
The announcement was delayed for more than two hours by reservations from
the former communist Party of the Democratic Left (PDS). Three members
accepted positions as ministers - Mr Vincenzo Visco, a prominent economist
as finance minister; Mr Augusto Barbera, a leading member of the referendum
movement, who takes charge of parliamentary relations; and Mr Luigi
Berlinguer as science minister.
A member of the enlarged steering committee of the PDS, Mr Berlinguer is a
cousin of the late Enrico Berlinguer, the Italian Communist party leader who
died in 1984 after breaking his party's ideological isolation. The new
minister is rector of the University of Siena, in Tuscany.
But Mr Achille Occhetto, the PDS leader, insisted the party would judge the
government by its programme. These reservations reflected the strong
internal divisions within the party over taking part in government after
being in opposition as the Communist party since 1948.
Among the other novelties is the presence of 38-year-old Mr Sandro Rutelli,
who recently failed to become elected the Green mayor of Rome, as
environment minister.
Of the portfolios that remain unchanged, the Treasury minister stays in the
hands of Mr Piero Barucci and the interior ministry continues to be headed
by the Christian Democrat, Mr Nicola Mancino. The foreign ministry was given
to the economist, Mr Nino Andreatta, who is the outgoing finance minister.
Mr Ciampi had earlier failed to persuade Mr Giuliano Amato, the outgoing
prime minister, to take the job. The new economic team includes Professor
Luigi Spaventa, a former fellow of All Souls, Oxford, as budget minister.
The cabinet, to be sworn in today, must now face the test of parliamentary
approval. But the presence of three ministers of the PDS, Greens and
Republicans ensures an ample parliamentary base beyond the outgoing
four-party coalition.
Andreotti signs up Bush adviser, Page 2
</TEXT>
