<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / German union votes to strike in east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IG METALL, Germany's powerful engineering union, won overwhelming support
yesterday for the first official strikes in eastern Germany for more than 60
years.
More than 86 per cent of eastern German steel employees affiliated to IG
Metall voted for strike action, which may start next week.
The vote was equally overwhelming among metal and electrical workers in
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania, and Saxony, the only two states balloted for
the sector.
Mr Franz Steinkuhler, the union's president, said the vote showed that 'all
dreams had died that IG Metall might not be prepared to fight in east
Germany'.
Gesamtmetall, the metal and electrical employers association, said higher
wages, coupled with low productivity, would 'dry up investment. This is
economically suicidal'.
Mr Herbert Hax, one of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's special economic advisers,
said: 'In the end, this (strike) would lead to a decline in investment,
which is urgently needed for rebuilding east Germany.'
Arbeitgeberverband Stahl, the steel employers' association, said IG Metall
was 'using eastern German workers as a means of boosting its flagging
support and power in the west'.
By using the threat of a strike, IG Metall wants to reinstate a contract,
ended last month by the employers, which would have equalised eastern and
western German wages by April 1994. The union says the employers broke the
contract not for economic reasons but to end the postwar system of
collective wage bargaining. The employers deny this.
The contract would have obliged employers to pay wage increases this year of
more than 20 per cent to the metal, electrical and steel sectors. The
employers are recommending about 9 per cent, matching the region's annual
inflation rate. Eastern German wages are about 70 per cent of western German
levels, but productivity lags behind western Germany by as much as 70 per
cent.
IG Metall, clearly encouraged by the outcome of the ballot, will hold a
special meeting today to decide where and when to hold the strikes. They
might start as early as May 3, but some of the employers' associations are
hoping the deadlock can be broken this weekend.
A meeting, called by the metal and electrical employers, will be held with
IG Metall tomorrow in the eastern state of Thuringia, even though the union
has repeatedly said it would negotiate only if employers reinstated the
contract.
The union said: 'This is not a real negotiation. In any case, wage policy is
made in Frankfurt' - IG Metall's federal headquarters. Gesamtmetall said
Cologne - its headquarters - would determine the status of the meeting.
However, an official of the steel employers said the meeting might move
towards a compromise: 'IG Metall cannot admit it is dropping its
preconditions.'
</TEXT>
