<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / The Lex Column: European telecoms
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Judging by yesterday's statement, the EC Commission has taken a look at the
slowly thawing European telecoms market and decided to stick it back in the
freezer for five years. While there were many fine words about openness and
competition, the defensive tone told the real story. The result may be a
compromise between foot-draggers like Deutsche Telekom and the hyperactive
BT, but it is evidently one which still embarrasses the Brussels
bureaucrats.
Even when nominal competition is allowed in 1998, freer markets may not
develop unless charges for connection to national systems are priced
correctly. National companies in Spain, Italy and Germany are still
absorbing cash updating their networks and will want to hold off financially
stronger competitors like BT as long as possible. Most probably, early
skirmishes will involve companies leasing lines from each other and
reselling the capacity to corporate customers; BT digging up the streets of
Frankfurt is much further off. Since margins are high there is plenty of
room for prices to fall. Continental companies will then have to press for
higher domestic charges because an effective cross-subsidy has been removed.
Meanwhile BT's restlessness will probably compel it to keep searching in the
US - hence the recent interest in acquiring EDS. If transatlantic
deregulation makes progress, BT's nascent cash pile seems likely to end up
in American hands. Whether it can find the right partner, however, remains
to be seen.
</TEXT>
