<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / The Lex Column: Total
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Foreign investors who hold 40 per cent of the French Total group may have
been irritated by the way it unilaterally increased its share capital by 7
per cent and took cross-shareholdings in three other businesses. Indeed
Anglo-Saxon annoyance may have partly accounted for the 2 per cent fall in
Total's share price yesterday. But that is how capitalism works in France.
In theory, shareholders should have little complaint about the financial and
industrial outcome for Total.
France's second biggest oil company will receive a net capital injection of
FFr2.5bn, which will cut gearing by 7 percentage points to 24 per cent.
There will be no dilution of earnings. Total will benefit from the sale of
its peripheral uranium interests to Cogema and should reap considerable
trading advantages through its link-up with Lyonnaise des Eaux-Dumez's
energy subsidiary. Its stronger balance sheet will permit more aggressive
exploration activities, perhaps in the North Sea and Indonesia. By pushing
Lasmo's share price up 3p yesterday, the UK market guessed at an alternative
route for development.
Though the French government has nominally reduced its direct shareholding
from 32 per cent to 5 per cent, it still wields considerable indirect
influence. Many French companies currently heading for privatisation will
doubtless see similar virtues in 'stabilising' their shareholder base, but
Total's share price fall is a reminder that, in a global market, such
behaviour carries a price.
</TEXT>
