<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / The Lex Column: The future tense
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
London had a worrying day yesterday. Heavy futures selling drove the FT-SE
100 down by 35 points. The gilts market decided the auction result was not
quite good enough and dropped over a point at the long end. There are benign
explanations for both developments. If US speculators really are selling
equity futures, the heat could be off quite quickly as their short positions
are closed. The gilts market could simply be coming back to earth after
allowing auction expectations to run away with themselves.
The trouble with the first point is that such bear raids only work in
markets that are anyway subject to some degree of uncertainty. As for the
second, the gilts market simply cannot afford to lose its composure when it
faces calls of Pounds 3bn as well, presumably, as another large auction
within the next month. Both markets have reason to worry about institutional
liquidity, but the attack on the equity market looks well-timed after this
week's economic news. It was not positive enough to change expectations of
corporate earnings, but it was sufficient to kill any lingering hopes of
lower interest rates.
With the gilt auctions now in full swing, the equity market has reached the
stage where it needs reassurance on government funding before it can see the
way ahead. That is not easy when the gold price is up and D-mark bonds are
weak. In the absence of a base rate cut which would steepen the yield curve,
a rising currency might attract overseas money into gilts. Disconcertingly,
though, sterling again failed to remain over DM2.50 yesterday despite a
larger than expected cut in the Bundesbank's money market repurchase rate.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
