<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Investors write off holdings in Accountancy Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS representing 40 per cent of the shares in Accountancy Television,
the late-night BBC weekly subscription programme produced by and for
accountants, have written off their holdings.
The Chartered Association of Certified Accountants states in its 1992 annual
report, released yesterday, that it has written off its entire Pounds
250,000 stake. Earlier this year, BPP Holdings, a financial training company
which holds shares worth Pounds 350,000, took similar action.
Mr David Bishop, president of the certified accountants, said his
organisation's policy was always to write off educational projects of this
sort, although the accounts do not make that statement.
BPP's write-off reflected what the company called 'a high-risk venture whose
future must be regarded as uncertain during this early critical period'.
Accountancy TV, which is broadcast by BBC Select, the late-night
subscription service, began broadcasting in October and has run into several
setbacks.
Mr Mike Lickiss, chairman of the company and a senior partner in Grant
Thornton, the accountancy firm, confirmed that the service was Pounds
300,000 behind projections.
He said he was still confident about the company but it would not make
profits until the end of 1994, at least six months beyond last year's
projections.
The other main BBC Select services for people in business and lawyers seem
to be going considerably better.
Mr Peter Brindley, chief executive of Legal Network Television, launched in
February, said last night: 'We are ahead of target. We have had a very good
launch.'
The company, whose shareholders are the College of Law, BBC Select and the
Law Society, broadcasts two half-hour programmes a week.
Mr Roy Bass, marketing director of the Executive Business Club, which
launched 10 months ago, said the service had taken Pounds 1.5m in
subscriptions and was on target.
Mr John Radcliffe, managing director of BBC Select, said he was happy with
progress but conceded that recession had made it more difficult to raise
money for new services.
Total shareholdings in Accountancy TV are Pounds 1.5m. The other investors
are BBC Select, the three chartered accountancy bodies covering the UK and
Ireland, and the Chartered Institute of Management Accountants.
There were initial differences between the five professional accountancy
bodies over the level of coverage provided to each of them. Difficulties
with the broadcast technology meant the company had to distribute some of
its early programmes by videotape.
In spite of initial optimistic projections that the company had attracted
interest from 11,000 potential subscribers, only a few more than 600 have
signed up.
Depsite market research which suggested the main audience was industry and
commerce the programmes were initially geared at least as much towards
accountants in practice.
The actual take-up proved, as predicted, to be mainly from business, and
Accountancy TV has had to modify its programmes to reflect that.
</TEXT>
