<PROFILE>_AN-DD2CUAEMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Leading Article: Dilemmas for Mr Lamont
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
IF NORMAN Lamont had known before the Budget what he knows now, would he
still have postponed his tax increases to next year? Some advised him to
increase taxes at once. He may already regret having ignored this advice.
The case for postponing tax increases in March was that they were likely to
extinguish the flickering flame of economic recovery. But there were also
arguments in favour of raising taxes immediately. The obvious argument was
that the fiscal position was unsustainable in the longer term, while any
deflationary impact of tax increases could be offset by reductions in
interest rates. An additional, under-emphasised, concern was about what
would happen if recovery were to come before the fiscal action. The
government would then rely on monetary policy as its sole disinflationary
instrument. The consequence could be appreciation of the exchange rate and
loss of competitiveness.
In its latest World Economic Outlook, the International Monetary Fund gives
concern about competitiveness little weight. But it is robust in its call
for a smaller budget deficit.
'The sustainability of the recovery,' argues the IMF, 'will depend on the
authorities' ability to safeguard the credibility of their anti-inflationary
commitment, especially in light of the potential inflationary consequences
of sterling's decline. This, in turn, depends critically on the adoption of
further measures, in the 1994 budget or even before (our emphasis), to
secure a faster reduction of the large budget deficit. . . . Any further
easing of monetary policy . . . should be resisted unless there is good
reason to believe that a further cut in interest rates would not endanger
the goal of containing inflation.'
Credibility undermined
The IMF is right on fiscal policy. The credibility of the anti-inflationary
commitment must be doubtful in the case of a government planning to borrow 9
per cent of gross domestic product this year and double its net debt, in
relation to GDP, in just half a decade. Credibility is further undermined by
willingness to borrow at 8 1/2 per cent over 20 years, when its target rate
of inflation in the medium term is 1-4 per cent and its announced aim is 'to
bring it down to the lower part of this range by the end of the present
parliament'.
More questionable is what the IMF has to say about monetary policy. Two
concerns might arise. The first is whether policy has provided enough
stimulation. The second is whether it is paying enough attention to
competitiveness.
Interest rates
The case for cuts in interest rates to stimulate domestic demand is weaker
than a month or two ago. Recovery is now unmistakable, while monetary data
are also showing a greenish light. Over the three months to March narrow
money (M0) grew at an annual rate of 9.9 per cent, while broad money growth
(M4) accelerated to 5.3 per cent. The former is well above its monitoring
range of 0 to 4 per cent, while the latter is at least within its wider
range of 3 to 9 per cent.
The difficult question is competitiveness. The exchange rate is the most
important relative price in the economy. Given the social and economic costs
of shifting resources into - and out of - industries producing tradable
goods and services, the government must not ignore the level of the exchange
rate or its variability. For a country with a current account deficit of 2
per cent of GDP at the trough of a recession, it seems particularly risky to
ignore competitiveness. But sterling has already appreciated from DM2.33 at
the end of February to just below DM2.50, while its trade-weighted effective
rate is up nearly 7 per cent.
The chancellor may well have been right to welcome this appreciation, since
the devaluation had left competitiveness at exceptional levels, at least by
standards of the 1980s. But appreciation should not be welcomed without
limits. Particularly if monetary growth seems subdued, the chancellor should
respond to any sustained appreciation by cutting interest rates. To do that
safely, however, he must also be more aggressive over fiscal policy next
time than he was in March.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
