FT  29 APR 93 / Observer: Voice off
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Whence comes the new pep in John Major's speeches? Even the weary ears of
Westminster have perked up at the tighter style, the steadier tone. Some of
his jokes are now even vaguely amusing.
Part of the reason, of course, is that his confidence is recovering along
with the economy and the approaching ratification of the Maastricht treaty.
Another, according to Downing Street officials, is that the PM is putting
more time into drafting his texts, though still not as much as the 50 or
more hours per spiel typically invested by his predecessor.
What the officials don't say, however, is that a helping hand is being lent
by sharp-witted civil servant Dominic Morris, now come from the Trade and
Industry Department to No 10, where he has joined Sarah Hogg's policy unit.
Just 39, and said to be a natural wordsmith, he has wrought his craft on
each of the premier's recent speeches.
He is no stranger to No 10, having worked there for four years under Lady
Thatcher. But the credit for spotting his talent belongs to the present
incumbent.
