<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Observer: Double act departs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
With the departure in May next year of Cazenove's joint senior partners John
Kemp-Welch and Anthony Forbes comes the end of one of the City's more
remarkable double acts.
In the mid-1980s, when the pukka stockbroker stood stubbornly aside from the
wave of mergers reshaping the surrounding landscape, many were inclined to
write it off as a force in the City. Today, as old rivals such as Hoare
Govett have been eclipsed, it looks stronger than ever.
Forbes, whose beat was corporate finance, and Kemp-Welch, the broker of the
pair, depart after 14 years atop a company that boasts more than 40 of the
FT-SE 100 companies among its clients.
'We could have gone on for a few more years, but it really wouldn't have
given our successor generation a fair crack of the whip,' explains the
ever-correct Kemp-Welch who, at 58, is two years older then Forbes.
Step up 49-year-old corporate finance specialist Mark Loveday. At Cazenove a
mere 27 years, and godson of former senior partner Antony Hornby, he
leapfrogs from seventh place on the letterhead, no mean feat in the status-
conscious world of a broking company which to the outsider sometimes looks
as if it has been stuck in a time-warp since the 1950s.
Two of those further up that all-important letterhead are David Mayhew, head
of the company's syndication department, and David Barnett, who runs the
secondary market operation. Kemp-Welch seems to think both will work closely
with Loveday, forming a virtual triumvirate at the top.
Its dominance of the domestic UK corporate broking market may be
unquestioned, but is Cazenove in danger of looking a shade anachronistic in
a world where more companies are looking to sell shares internationally
rather than in just one market?
On past experience it would be wrong to write the firm off.
</TEXT>
