<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Letter: Green shoots too late to help the bankrupt (1)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Ms GILL HANKEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, We are now officially out of the recession say Prime Minister John
Major and Chancellor Norman Lamont, and the British people are expected to
be grateful for this achievement of their government.
Do they expect congratulations? When is this government going to give
credit, never mind congratulations, to all those entrepreneurs and business
people who have given their all and lost everything thanks to their
policies.
This is just about the final insult. Will they ever acknowledge the
suffering they have caused to small and medium-sized businesses, to the
hardworking and honest people who are now bankrupt because they have tried
and failed?
They expect to be hailed as heroes but the failed businessmen and
businesswomen are treated as criminals for their efforts.
I hope, but do not believe, that the 'green shoots of recovery' are
appearing. Many businesses are still going down, thousands are losing their
jobs, more people than ever are being made bankrupt; calls for support and
advice to our association are still increasing alarmingly.
Gill Hankey,
national officer,
The Bankruptcy Association,
4 Johnson Close,
Lancaster LA1 5EU
</TEXT>
