<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Arts: The survivalist's unholy Communion - Cinema
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALIVE (15)
Empire
THE MYSTERY OF EDWIN DROOD (12)
MGM Shaftesbury Ave
MEDITERRANEO (15)
Curzon Mayfair, Screen on the Green
RUBY CAIRO (15)
Plaza
NATIONAL LAMPOON'S LOADED WEAPON 1 (PG)
MGMs West End
Before 'You are what you eat' there was 'You eat what you are.' The 1972
Andes plane crash brought cannibalism, man's oldest form of nouvelle
cuisine, into everyone's sitting-room. Consuming your own kind turned from
taboo to talking point; Piers Paul Read's book Alive became a survivalist's
guide to anthropophagy; and now the film pours God all over the debate,
suggesting that the diet of the 20-odd Uruguayans who crash-landed in an
aircraft while flying over snow-topped crags to a rugger match in Chile was
a Communion ritual in a world large with divinity.
'It's magnificent] It's God]' cries Nando (Ethan Hawke) from the final
mountain peak of his trek to find rescue. God stalks the dialogue and
imagery. And we begin with John Malkovich in stubble-bearded close-up as an
ageing Andes survivor, purring thoughts of God into camera.
We do not need all this nudging to see the miraculous in the story. The
group's young saviour, Nando Parrado, came back almost literally from the
dead. (He was counted among the corpses immediately after the crash). And
what better argument to persuade Catholics to eat meat sliced from their
dead friends than to invoke the cannibalistic implications of Communion
itself.
Alive the movie is thrilling whenever it allows the miraculous to breathe
freely and does not strap it to a symbolist life-support machine. The crash
itself may be the best ever filmed. You clutch your cinema seat while a
crunching, booming soundtrack spins your stomach and the screen is a chaos
of screaming bodies, snapping wings, and passenger seats (plus passengers)
sucked through the gaping hole where the tail once was.
Other visceral moments cling to the memory. An avalanche, complete with
ear-splitting rumble and a high-speed tracking-shot that thunders us into
the broken plane to overpower the survivors. (Is this the first
snow-viewpoint shot in history?) And the camera's final, moving,
preposterously inspirational swoop from icy crags to green valley as the
team's rescue-trekkers sight salvation.
The film itself has lows as well as highs. That Alive the movie would be a
play-off between ripping yarn and religious fable we suspected. Co-produced
by Disney, its quest for the family audience requires that the eating of
human flesh is made to seem decent and even sanctified. Delicate scoops from
a frozen buttock yield something resembling smoked turkey slices - even I
would eat them - and no other body part is touched. The real survivors, we
know, ate everything, including stewed-up brains, organs and intestines.
With the lies of omission go lies of commission. Characters hanging off
sheer cliff-edges and indulging in death-defying toboggan rides I do not
remember from the book. Perhaps their Boy's Own hyperbolism testifies to
director Frank Marshall's previous history as a producer/second-unit
director for Master Steven Spielberg.
Yet the greatness of the story itself keeps jumping up to trounce the
trivial. With Marshall's young actors as good as their near-impossible
challenge allows (too many characters for any one to be sculpted in depth),
the ragged splendour of their ordeal finally becomes as elemental,
all-conquering and ugly-beautiful as the landscape around them. We begin by
regretting the injections of God and the shortfalls in realism. (No mistings
of breath in supposedly sub-zero climes; no sense of vast acoustical space
round the post-dubbed voices). We stammer brief protests at the cliffhanging
hokum. But by the end the game of resistance is up. Alive has come alive
with the sound of a great human story slowly condensing into a great human
myth.
*****
Charles Dickens left his last novel, The Mystery Of Edwin Drood, unfinished
at his death. Enter posterity, bearing sackfuls of surmise. For 120 years
the Drood-sleuths have tried to piece together the evidence. Young Edwin -
was he murdered? His opium-crazed, jealous-in-love uncle Mr Jasper - did he
do it? And what of Durdles and Crisparkle and Grewgious - who knows to what
madness men can be driven by the burden of bearing wacky Dickensian names?
Writer-director Timothy Forder knows all about wacky names as creator of the
TV cartoon series Murun Buchstansangur. His film of Drood is the work of an
animator fallen on live action. Actors, being less easily ordered about than
sketches, can look helplessly two-dimensional if given the wrong carrots and
sticks.
Here Robert Powell's gaunt-necked Mr Jasper (a Carrot refugee on a stick),
Glyn Houston's one-note, high-coloured Grewgious (looking as if someone
should loosen his shirt collar), Jonathan Phillips's Drood (just a pretty
face), Andrew Sachs's Durdles (not even that) somnambulate through the dim
lighting, tension-free screenplay and mise-en-scene as wooden as the
duty-Dickensian exposed timbers. Where are the Gothic frissons? Where the
bleak, black sense of a Victorian era riddled with disguise and
double-standard?
In this wet squib of a film, I most enjoyed Freddie Jones as Mayor Sapsea:
an un-dampenable actor here yawing and hamming as if no one has told him
that the style du jour is plainspun recitative rather than Droodian grand
guignol.
Gabriele Salvatore's Mediterraneo won last year's Best Foreign Film Oscar:
an honour traditionally conferred on movies whose plot and concept are
simple enough for Academy members to grasp with one side of their brain
while the other explodes under the unfamiliar impact of subtitles.
Here are eight Italian soldiers stranded on a Greek island in the second
world war. Helped by a broken radio and a bomb-destroyed battleship, they
unwind into hedonism as the years pass. They form relationships with the
local women and donkeys. The leader paints frescoes in the church. The
squad's shy youngster falls in love with the village prostitute. In short
they go native. When 'rescue' finally comes, it is in the shape of what seem
to be the same short-trousered British Naval personnel who rescued the
children in Lord Of The Flies.
It is charming, but is it art? In a year that saw authentically
mind-stretching 'foreign' films by Zhang Yimou, Chen Kaige, Jacques Rivette,
Bertrand Tavernier, this gentle, photogenic, all-human-life yarn could be an
NC Hunter play transplanted to package-hols land. But then in a Hollywood
Academician's life perhaps a little is as good as a feast.
Anything would be a feast compared with Ruby Cairo. Miss Andie McDowell is
going around the world piecing together clues that may lead to the
rediscovery of her 'dead' husband (Viggo Mortensen), an international
smuggler. But why are we the audience following her? It cannot be for
suspense - there is none. It cannot be for comedy - nobody is laughing. And
if it is for romance - Miss McDowell meets charity worker Liam Neeson on a
wharf and then keeps re-meeting him - why do we need that other
husband-hunting plot at all?
Short answer: we don't. Long answer: director Graeme Clifford (Frances),
writer Robert Dillon (Muscle Beach Party) and Miss McDowell (nothing
interesting since sex, lies and videotape) had time on their hands in
not-too-busy careers and thought they might knock off all available genres
in one movie.
Last and least, National Lampoon's Loaded Weapon 1. Here the Lampoon gang,
seizing and asset-stripping the Lethal Weapon series, add a '1' as if urging
everyone to salivate at the thought of more. Most of us, after 80 minutes of
this, will be crying out for less. Emilio Estevez and Samuel L. Jackson are
the white cop/black cop heroes; there is many a stalled or tailspinning
Airplane-ish gag; and writer-director Gene Quintano is trampled underfoot as
the guest stars (William Shatner, Charlie Sheen, sexologist Dr Joyce
Brothers, Uncle Tom Cobbley) try to leave the plane by the emergency doors.
</TEXT>
