<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Arts: Gala performance of Love in the Country
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There will be a gala performance of Love in the Country, with music by
Anthony Bowles, at the Duke of York's theatre in St Martin's Lane, London,
on Sunday May 2. Meanwhile, the show is having a try-out at the Almeida in
Islington until Saturday, writes Malcolm Rutherford.
Bowles was the musical director of many West End successes including Evita
and Irma la Douce. He died in March before the development of his prime work
was completed. Love in the Country was first performed at LAMDA in 1970 when
Bowles was a teacher there. The story is loosely based on Daphnis and Chloe
in the Isle of Lesbos. The book is in rhymed couplets and, like the lyrics,
written by Mike Alfreds, his long-time collaborator. Most of that is
surprisingly weak. The music, however, is pretty and clever throughout. In
the last 20 minutes the show takes off in a glorious display of wit. If the
Almeida performances can be treated as extended rehearsals, there may be
something to look forward to at the Duke of York's.
</TEXT>
