<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Arts: Stretching the possible - London Concerts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It has taken a decade for London to be given a second performance of Robin
Holloway's Second Concerto for Orchestra, Op. 40 - the first, which itself
came three long years after the Glasgow premiere in 1979, was at the 1982
Proms. There are no doubt hard practical reasons why our orchestras have
from the first steered clear of this huge (40-minute-long), simply
astonishing piece of sustained compositional virtuosity - for a start
because it is hair-raisingly difficult to put together, play and rehearse.
But they provide no real excuse: the work needs to have seeped into
orchestral consciousness, extending players' and listeners' range of the
possible, stretching their and our sense of 20th-century musical fantasy as,
given half a chance, it undoubtedly would. Never mind: Monday's performance
at the Royal Festival Hall by the BBC Symphony under Oliver Knussen -
dedicatee of the Second Concerto - was on all counts a triumphant revival,
solving difficulty after technical difficulty with exactly the combination
of formidable exactitude and insouciant wit the music requires.
The main point about this concerto for orchestra was proved beyond argument:
that it is at once a three-movement showpiece in the honourable Bartok
tradition, concerned to make a brilliant showing of every orchestral
department, and a kind of 'music-drama for orchestra' boldly exploring
little-charted expressive territories - among them, a film-like lapping of
wave upon wave of musical imagery on the shore of a structure itself only
gradually revealed.
Influences abound (Wagner, Strauss, Debussy, Ravel, Stravinsky etc); madcap
snatches of the Chopin Barcarolle and 'Arrivederci Roma' continually flit
across the musical screen; a 'continuo' group of north African-style
percussion disciplines the content with its special fierce glitter.
Eventually, a transition built up of freely notated solo cadenzas arrives to
provide a Dawn Chorus to all the earlier dream-outpourings; this gives way
to a finale firmly pulled together to show that Holloway's allusive,
kaleidoscopic style, far from being promiscuously unleashed or loose in
purpose, has from the first been unified, and capable of exhilarating
resolution.
In addition to dazzling every ear with Holloway, Knussen and the BBC had
already put us permanently in their debt with the London premiere of Aaron
Copland's 1922 ballet Grohg, an early score long lost and only recently
rediscovered, packed with wonderful inventions to be mined in all the more
famous Copland achievements - and a badly-needed re-examination of the
toughly trenchant Inscape (1967), his last significant piece.
BBC Symphony Orchestra at the Royal Festival Hall: concert recorded by Radio
3 for future transmission.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
