<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Arts: Small-scale Swiss attractions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The English Chamber Orchestra's attractive Swiss programme on Monday failed
by a long way to attract the audience it deserved. One hoped that the Swiss
music-lovers on hand took no offence. The trouble was, simply, that no big
works coming out of Switzerland (except a very few whole-evening ones -
operas, oratorios - which demand larger forces) have come into the
international repertoire. Many people have heard and enjoyed a little
Honegger, and maybe Frank Martin's Petite Symphonie Concertante, and just
possibly something by Othmar Schoeck; but a concert devoted to those three
composers will not pull a crowd.
And certainly not at Barbican prices, when its natural home would be the
smaller, thriftier Queen Elizabeth Hall. In fact Martin's PSC was the
opening piece here, and very well played too. It exercised its familiar,
slightly clammy grip, with a hint of inexorable mechanism. Howard Griffiths
has already spent a dozen years conducting in Switzerland and his soloists
on piano, harp and harpsichord were the faithful Yonty Solomon, Thelma Owen
and Ian Watson, balanced with excellent clarity.
Martin's sound-world has a quite particular glint, and his pattern-building
a severe hieratic air. It really is time that we had a full-scale production
of his fine, dark Shakespeare opera on The Tempest. Honegger's highly
conscious constructions reveal a formal sensibility much like his, though
Honegger liked pithier, more resiny sounds.
Thus his war-time Second Symphony for strings, which ended the concert: a
neat, modestly original ground-plan, with a doomy central passacaglia and a
trumpet ('optional') to brighten its final chorale. As often in Honegger,
that seems a kind of backtracking to public piety - Protestant at heart,
surely, despite his still-popular Jeanne d'Arc au bucher - by way of
solemnly joining hands. The trumpet was admirable; the racing strings might
have enjoyed one more rehearsal.
For many listeners, Schoeck's early Violin Concerto will have been the
discovery of the evening. Plainly it occupies youthful, dewy Richard Strauss
territory, with little harmonic tweaks where later Schoeck grew into ripe
expressive complications; but the solo part is eager and songful. Lydia
Mordkovich delivered it with vital enthusiasm. There was also a surprise
bonbon in the 58-year-old Rolf Urs Ringger's 'con slancio', a five-minute
piece of honest, almost up-to-date engineering with vibes and much knitting
of short phrases. It generated some brief, effective splashes, but no
continuing ripples.
Sponsored by Reuters
</TEXT>
