<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / People: BT's Romeril departs for Xerox in US
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Barry Romeril, BT's group finance director since 1988 and one of the most
powerful men in Britain's telecommunications behemoth, has resigned to take
up the post of chief financial officer at Xerox Corporation in the US.
Romeril, 49, is no stranger to north America. In previous incarnations, as
assistant treasurer of ICI Americas and US chief financial officer for BTR
Inc, he built up several years' experience of American accounting practices.
Yesterday he said he was sorry to be leaving BT but the opportunity at Xerox
was attractive and fitted in with a desire to return to work once more in
the US.
The parting with BT seems entirely amicable. Romeril does not join Xerox
until June 30, and Iain Vallance, BT chairman, yesterday paid him a glowing
tribute. It does, however, leave a significant gap in BT's senior
management; the company said yesterday it had not yet decided on his
replacement.
Romeril, born in Jersey in the Channel Islands and educated at Oxford
University where he read economics, was seen on his appointment to BT as one
of a 'new guard' of young British managers with a reputation for cutting
costs. It was a skill he was to use year after year in improving BT's
profitability.
At Xerox Romeril will become an executive vice president and a member of
chairman Paul Allaire's corporate office. He takes over a post that has been
vacant since 1990 when Stuart Ross became chairman of Xerox Financial
Services. Xerox clearly has need of Romeril's cost-cutting experience; it
pulled out of financial services earlier this year at an estimated cost of
Dollars 3bn.
</TEXT>
