<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / People: Bahl takes over from Foster at Equal Opportunities
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Equal Opportunities Commission's new chairman from June 14 will be
Kamlesh Bahl, 36, currently company secretary and manager of legal services
with Data Logic, the computing services company.
Bahl (right) takes over from Joanna Foster (far right), who has done the job
since 1988 and is now off to run the UK's contribution to the United Nations
Year of the Family.
This was the first time the EOC appointment, which is for three years, has
been openly advertised in the national press. The Department of Employment,
which oversees the EOC, says Bahl was appointed from a strong list of over
80 candidates for the job. The post pays just over Pounds 30,000 for three
days a week - for the remainder of the time Bahl will continue at Data
Logic, but as a consultant, rather than in her current role.
The EOC, which has its headquarters in Manchester, has a budget of about
Pounds 5.8m and about 160 staff. The day-to-day running of the organisation
and management matters are handled by the chief executive, Valerie Amos,
while the chairman concentrates on policy issues and tends to present the
EOC's public face.
Bahl is well-versed in equality issues and the workings of committees of the
great and the good; she is a member of the Law Society's council, sits on
its race relations committee, and was the first woman to chair the society's
commerce and industry group. Like many women in the crustier professions,
she has sometimes had to deal with the accusation of being a 'token'
appointee.
Her other activities include being a council member of the National
Association of Health Authorities and Trusts, and sitting on the race
relations minorities advisory committee of the Lord Chancellor's judicial
studies board.
It is also widely believed that Bahl, through Law Society and BBC
connections, is the model for Usha Gupta, the Asian lawyer in the Archers on
Radio 4.
Meanwhile, Joanna Foster, the departing EOC chairman, describes her
five-year tenure as 'an extraordinary experience'. Her immediate priorities
are 'to get fit, to unpack books from last year's house move, and to do what
I have spent much of the past five years expecting everyone else to do - get
a good balance into my life between work and family'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
