<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): The clear contender
 -Beer is the latest product to get the transparent treatment in the battle
for US market share
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It looks like gin and tonic with a frothy head. It tastes like . . . well,
some sort of a fizzy drink.
This is Clear Beer, a new product which Miller Brewing, the second largest
beer producer in the US and part of the giant Philip Morris group, launched
this month in selected markets.
Consumers in Austin (Texas), Richmond (Virginia) and Minneapolis (Minnesota)
were able to purchase the bottled brew immediately. A 12-ounce can version
will be available next month.
Why, it might be asked, should anyone even contemplate marketing a
colourless ale? The answer is twofold. In part, the new brew is a response
to the large but moribund US beer market where innovation is essential to
sales growth. In part, however, Miller is seeking to capitalise on one of
the hottest US marketing themes: clear products.
The US beer market is - if the term can be excused - flat. Total sales
volume has been static at around 190m barrels for five years and the
brewers' need to grab market share has become paramount.
For years, the motor within the sector has been sales of lower-calorie
'light' beer, to the point where aggregate volume for the three main brands
in this subsector - Miller Lite, Coors Light and Bud Light - topped 40m
barrels in 1992. That was only slightly below the 46.8m barrels of Budweiser
 -the nation's top-selling brew - which disappeared down American throats.
Miller's theory is that the new clear product will offer a 'full beer
flavour', but be perceived as lacking the 'heaviness' which the traditional
amber nectar imparts.
But the beer has the same alcohol content as any ordinary American beer, and
is made from a traditional mix of hops, barley and cereal grains. Yet the
colourless pint delivers a lower carbohydrate count - about half that of a
conventional beer. This, plus the beer's appearance, may persuade drinkers
that it is actually a 'lighter' product.
A little surprisingly, the promotional campaign surrounding the new beverage
is more concerned with persuading consumers that 'clear beer' is really
beer, than with playing up its wholesome image.
'Great beer-drinking beer' is the advertising tagline devised by New York
agency Cliff Freeman - with repetition of the word 'beer' designed to
emphasis the drink's authenticity. Ears of corn are also prominent on the
label design.
Whether drinkers take to Clear Beer only time will tell. But the product's
launch does point up the very discernable marketing trend towards colourless
products in the US which is now beginning to appear in UK.
This is usually viewed as an outcrop of the pro-health, pro-environment
concerns which have been a driving force in the consumer goods sector in the
1990s. According to New Product News, in Chicago, about three dozen clear
products hit the supermarket shelves last year, ranging from mouthwashes to
rubbish bags.
Included in the list are offerings from some of the nation's biggest
consumer goods companies. In December, for example, PepsiCo launched
'Crystal Pepsi', a clear, no-preservative version of the traditional soft
drink. Coca-Cola is retaliating with 'Tab Clear', its own colourless cola.
Meanwhile, in the toiletries area, Gillette has introduced 'Cleargel
deodorant'. Procter &amp; Gamble is making a clear Ivory dishwashing liquid  - a
product which has traditionally been 'milky-cream' - and selling it in
transparent containers. Colgate-Palmolive, a rival detergents manufacturer,
is doing likewise. There is even a clear petrol produced by Amoco. Though
this is not actually a new product, the gasoline has been renamed 'Crystal
Clear Amoco Ultimate' and is being promoted more actively and distributed
more widely.
Many of these products have been on the market for too short a time for any
sensible assessment of their selling power to be made.
Most manufacturers admit that curiosity may be a factor in driving up
post-launch sales, and market research firms such as A C Nielson decline to
supply figures on market share for recently launched products.
That said, there are some early indications that shoppers are proving
responsive. The trade press, for example, has suggested that Crystal Pepsi
may have taken about 2.4 per cent of the large US soft drinks market in the
first few months since its nationwide launch. Pepsi says that figure - if
correct - 'would make us ecstatic'. The company's goal is to have the
product command a 2 per cent market share by the end of this year, which
would equate to sales of more than Dollars 1bn. Pepsi is currently
considering whether to launch the product overseas.
P&amp;G, which replaced its entire Ivory dishwashing liquid line with the new
clear version last summer, also says that both sales and market share have
increased since then, although it declines to give numbers.
But nearly all of these manufacturers are savvy enough to suggest that the
'clearness' of the product is merely a visual means of emphasising
underlying product enhancements.
P&amp;G, for example, claims that the 'colourless' revamp of its dishwashing
liquid accompanied a product reformulation, and that this enhanced Ivory's
'grease-cutting' ability.
Palmolive calls its colourless detergent 'Palmolive Sensitive Skin' - to
stress the additional cosmetic benefits.
Pepsi, meanwhile, notes that Crystal is also a no-preservative, no-caffeine
product. 'Yes, it's a clear product,' says the company, 'but that's just one
of its marketing attributes. Making a clear drink was not our primary aim.'
Clarity, however, does not come cheap. Since these products generally claim
benefits over their traditional counterparts, with lack of colour being used
to emphasise this fact, they tend to cost more. For example, a 22-oz bottle
of Sensitive Skin dishwashing liquid costs Dollars 2.29 in a Manhattan
supermarket, compared with Dollars 2.19 for the traditional version. Virtue,
in short, has its price.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
