<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Business Schools (12): Ambivalence rules in the UK
 -The progress of business ethics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACROSS THE business schools of Britain, small lights illuminating the
presence of classrooms teaching ethics are beginning to glimmer. Their beams
so far remain very faint.
Business ethics is beginning to appear in the curriculum. It has grown from
a strong base in the US into a topic being taken seriously on campuses
elsewhere around the world.
There is now a European Business Ethics Network of academics and
practitioners, and a fledgling journal, counterbalancing the much more
substantial literature being generated in North America.
Recent corporate scandals, not least the fracas between British Airways and
Virgin, have served to highlight the need to take the subject seriously. But
it is ironic that it is the business sector - which has been behaving in
ways ethically questionable - which has begun to address the matter of how
acceptable such behaviour is, and to make amends.
Academia might have been expected to have taken a lead, launching courses
and raising questions in the classroom. In fact, much of the impetus seems
to have come from business. A growing number of companies' annual reports
make references to corporate governance.
An analysis by the Institute of Business Ethics last summer showed that
nearly 30 per cent of large companies have a written ethical code, covering
topics such as relations with employees and customers, and sexual
harassment.
Even in teaching, some companies have seized the initiative by launching
their own internal sessions to consider the subject. For example, Mr John
Drummond of Integrity Works, a London-based consultancy on ethical matters,
has just completed work with National Westminster Bank to develop an ethical
code and a series of associated procedures for the bank in consultation with
its employees.
But perhaps most significantly, the last few months have seen the creation
of no fewer than three academic chairs in the subject, all at the
instigation of companies.
For example, in April 1992 Drake Beam Morin (DBM), the out-placement
consultants, funded a chair in corporate governance at Leeds University, now
occupied by Mr Thomas Clarke. Then the Co-Operative Bank announced the
creation, with its support, of a chair of corporate responsibility at
Manchester Business School, to which Mr Brian Harvey has been appointed.
And Dixons, the electrical retailer, donated Pounds 1m last July to the
London Business School, to establish a chair of business ethics and social
responsibility.
Mr Stanley Kalms, Dixons' chairman, says: 'You started wondering, as you
watched the attitudes being formed in the 1980s, can this be right? There
were too many two-dimensional, cardboard people, worried only about
themselves and acquisitions. Intelligence said this can't be enough.'
He sees the need for serious study of the topic. 'A lot of people reject the
concept of ethics and talk instead about integrity. This is a philistine
approach. I come from the integrity school. But I realised that was just
using words. It's no good taking your own standards of integrity and
assuming everyone in your organisation shares them.'
In spite of these business gestures in the direction of change, the response
from academia remains muted. There is no sign yet of an appointment to the
London Business School post - which partly reflects the lack of suitable
candidates for such a position in the UK.
There is still considerable ambivalence about teaching the subject, let
alone how it should be taught: as an integrated topic or a separate module.
In fact, Mr Kalms says he first offered the money to the economics
department at the London School of Economics - but it rejected the donation,
arguing that such a subject properly belonged in the philosophy department.
That attitude is strongly rejected by the small new breed of business school
ethics faculty. 'It's very important to build the ethical dimensions into
each subject and not isolate with some semi-cleric delivering sermons on the
side,' says Mr Clarke from Leeds.
He says the philosophy department is working with the business school to
develop an MA course in business policy and ethics, designed for 'the
cerebral, reflective manager.'
But he concedes: 'You'd be hard put to find a business ethics course in the
UK at the moment. It's a guest lecture thing. I feel it will move from an
optional extra on MBA courses to part of a corporate responsibility core
subject. We will begin slowly to emulate what's happening in the US.'
He argues that during the 1980s, business schools over-enthusiastically
threw out subjects such as sociology from their curricula. A contrary mood
is only now developing.
One example is at the Cranfield Institute of Technology. Mr Shai Vyakarnam,
a lecturer, says his optional course on ethics in business decisions has
attracted 21 of the school's 160 MBA students this year.
Recognition of the current dearth of courses is widespread, matched only by
a modest optimism for the future. 'Trickle is the right word,' says Mr Rob
Gray, head of the accounting and business finance department at the
University of Dundee. 'But it is the issue of the future.'
Mr Harvey from Manchester Business School says: 'Everybody is nibbling away
at it. My feeling is that they haven't got very far.' (That includes his own
department which, he says, has yet to offer business ethics as an option.)
But he sees demand growing for the topic, with particular interest from
executives in 'how to manage to maintain a grip on the corporate ethos and
brand when you have empowered managers focused on the bottom line.'
Business has clearly thrown down the gauntlet in the courts of academia.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8244 Business and Secretarial Schools.
    P8331 Job Training and Related Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
