<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Business Schools (10): Boom has given way to a new
caution - Adrian Furnham analyses some noticeable trends in management and
business training in the 1990s
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ADRIAN FURNHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR ALL the impact of recession, training budgets remain large. Companies
and public sector organisations buy in (or have in-house) training
departments, centres and even country castles to run training courses for
their staff.
Courses cover all sorts of topics: induction to the organisation, specific
job-related or 'people' skills (assertiveness, negotiation) and
culture-change developmental workshops aimed at middle or senior management.
But economic downturns mean that training budgets look easy targets for
cuts; products and technical innovations mean training has to respond to
different needs; demographic changes in the internal (employees) and
external (purchasing) customers mean that programmes soon become redundant.
Many training departments also suffer a poor image. They are seen as a
backwater of personnel itself; a refuge for the incompetent.
There are some noticeable trends in management and business training in the
1990s The 1980s boom, with its inevitable heroes and fads, has given way to
a new caution. Different themes have begun to emerge which are likely to
endure. Though not all apparent in all organisations, at least seven themes
may be remarked.
Learning not Training: Training is about acquiring specific skills; learning
is more concerned with general principles. Training is for the here-and-how:
company-specific; highly practical, even pragmatic. Learning has less
immediate application but is designed to be more useful in various contexts.
Companies have preferred training because it is believed to be more cost
effective. Many firms do not believe that their task is to provide a rather
general university-based education. That, they argue, is a luxury which
managers can buy for themselves, but more and more companies see benefit in
the well-educated manager; the intelligent generalist.
Because there is nothing as practical as good theory they send their people
off to acquire an MBA, or on longer developmental courses. The opportunity
for learning (as opposed to training) may actually help staff retention in
these firms, and might even encourage better applicants.
Some companies approach business schools to teach their own client-derived
syllabus, but taught and approved by the university. So the manager gets
organisation-approved education plus a degree.
A less provincial, chauvinistic, ethnocentric perspective: We now have a
global market, an international work-force and multi-national products.
Management has had to take this into consideration. Cosy 'we-they' stories,
case histories from local companies and a homogeneous work-force are things
of the past.
All managers need a wider perspective - not just pan-European, but the
global market. Hence the focus on cultural differences, and comprehensive
briefings on how companies in other countries do things. The 'little
Englander' trainer, like the vulgar American consultant, faces extinction.
Euro-sceptics are not welcome in the training centre. All managers are being
encouraged to be multi-lingual and comfortable in cross-cultural
communication.
Competency-led training: - Despite the vagueness of the concept of
competency, many organisations have been forced to think through exactly
which skills, abilities and traits they require of their managers. Having
done this they are frequently much more focused on what sort of training is
needed.
In the past, trainers provided what was thought appropriate - or, more
prosaically, what they could offer. Now they are being required to integrate
the training programme into the company's overall competence-led training or
human resource strategy.
Courses which do not fit may be jettisoned. Others may have to be created to
meet the needs of the proposed strategy.
In this sense training follows strategy, although competencies are often
defined so vaguely that the trainers can easily adapt what they have to
satisfy their clients in the board room.
Team building rather than leadership: If the 1980s was the 'me' decade and
the 1990s is the 'we' decade, how is this reflected in management training?
Nearly everyone works in groups; business success is, we are told, dependent
not on individual but on teams. It really is true that a chain is only as
strong as its weakest link.
Heterogeneous teams - those with overall ability but whose members each have
different skills, preferences and approaches that complement each other, do
best.
Just as people may have to be trained to become leaders, they may also have
to be trained to be followers. Training programmes now focus on how to
build, sustain and manage a team; how to assess your favourite and most
comfortable role when operating a team; how to select individuals with a
team in mind, and how to be a better team member.
Virtual-reality training: Trainers have always worried about the
'generalisability' of training - that is, whether what you learn on courses
in comfortable hotels or cosy training centres actually gets applied, let
alone remembered, in the real work setting. The more realistic or similar
the training environment to the work environment, the less, by definition,
is there a problem of generalisation.
Airlines spend on simulators. Trainers, too, are now considering training in
situ - on the shop floor, in the executive office or in the sales room.
Though this may cause some inconvenience or even danger to customer or
equipment, it is thought worth it.
Shadowing - observing someone on the job, is becoming more popular and,
supposedly, a useful teaching aid. (This development may be bad news for
hotels making money from chalk-and-talk seminars.)
Using managers as trainers: It is not only because of the expense of
staffing a permanent training department, or calling in egotistical
consultants, that there is a trend for managers to become trainers
themselves. People rightly expect that in some circumstances managers can
act as trainers, because they are the ones with the most relevant knowledge.
Most managers have the time and the skill to become explicit trainers rather
than simply people to be imitated. They can do a very useful job. Some
organisations have attempted to re-define job titles to reflect this. (Thus
supervisors may become 'coaches'; and managers 'the support staff.'
Using subordinate feedback: Most managers are used to being appraised by
their superiors, and occasionally by their peers. Trainers, on the other
hand, are used to being rated by their course attenders.
Many organisations are even considering using subordinate ratings, not only
as useful feedback technique in training, but also a possible source of data
for staff appraisals. More and more trainers now are using upward or
'bottom-up' feedback compared to the more traditional downward appraisal.
But pity the middle aged, middle-brow, middle manager who, as part of his
training, has to learn business French; go on outdoor training courses to be
a good team member; is called a marketing coach; and is rated on his
performance by a youth just out of a 'new' university business school.
Adrian Furnham is head of the Business Psychology Unit at University
College, London.
</TEXT>
<XX>
