<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Business Schools (7): Tempo steps into Europe -
Cranfield's emphasis is on the practical
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CRANFIELD is about to change its title from 'institute of technology' to
'university'. It is a sad commentary on the status of vocationally-oriented
higher education institutions in Britain that Cranfield finally felt it had
to join the crowd. The assumption of university titles by the former
polytechnics was the last straw.
'If we could have sold our name like MIT (the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology at Boston, in the US), we would have stuck to it,' says Professor
Leo Murray, Cranfield School of Management's ebullient director.
'But with every primary school in the country now calling itself a
university, people simply don't understand what we are about.'
Murray is adamant as to what his school, the largest of Cranfield
university-to-be's four centres, is about. 'The practical and applied is our
concern: high quality training to produce effective managers - whether on
our MBA courses, or in our growing short-course market.'
'Management is an intensely practical subject,' he says, deflecting
criticism of the School's mediocre performance in the Universities Funding
Council's recent assessment of research quality. 'Our research is
unambiguously applied: grand theory really has little or nothing to do with
management studies as they should be.'
'The emphasis is, and should be, on practical training for practical
problems; and research into issues that will help students and managers to
do that.'
It is for such practical skills that a steady stream of top executives and
upwardly-mobile young managers drive to rural Bedfordshire, or make the
20-minute cab ride from Milton Keynes.
Cranfield started life in 1946 as a school of aeronautical engineering - on
the site, and in the buildings, of a wartime aerodrome, appropriately
enough. Until Sir Norman Foster designed for the school a magnificent
steel-and-glass library, which was opened last year, the campus resembled a
prisoner-of-war camp; now that the giant hangar-style library is complete
and open, it looks as if might house the Royal Flight.
Murray does 'not for a moment' doubt that his charge is among the elect of
the business school fraternity. He is particularly proud of Cranfield's
range of tailored-courses, and of the 'Cranfield 2000' project to keep its
MBA up-to-date.
For the moment, Cranfield 2,000 means 'breaking down the old baronies' which
divide the MBA into hard-and-fast subjects (marketing, finance and so on)
and, instead, 'conceiving of it in the context of the company, where the
various specialisms inter-connect and overlap.' In everyday terms, this
means laying stress on group working and company case studies; and a growing
emphasis on international business - together with the skills that go with
it, including languages.
Like most UK business schools, behind the rhetoric of 'internationalisation'
Cranfield is Britannic to the core. Language training apart, Murray's
response is not, a la London Business School, to seek to change radically
from within, but to forge new partnerships from without.
The imminent creation of a Top European Management Programme ('Tempo') is a
significant step on the way: a consortium of Cranfield, Group ESC Lyon,
Instituto de Empresa in Barcelona and USW Schloss Gracht in Germany, Tempo
is intended to enable each of the four to design tailored in-company
programmes drawing on the resources and facilities of other members.
Cranfield is also working with Groupe ESC Lyon and Koblenz University's
Forum Mittelstand to launch a joint European Management programme -
'designed', says the blurb, 'to teach participants to Think European and Act
Local.'
Numbers on the part- and full-time MBA courses are roughly equal, at between
140 and 160 apiece. The part-time course is not an add-on: equal resources
are devoted to it, with special efforts made to strengthen links with
sponsoring employers. These include regular 'parents' days' (Cranfield's
jargon) when sponsors are invited to spend a day at the school to review
progress and discuss suitable project work for the last stage of the course.
However, the MBA is playing a declining role in the School's funding.
Last year three-quarters of its income came from other sources - not much
from the government, which accounted for less than 10 per cent, but mainly
from research and contracts (27 per cent) and, most important of all, short
courses (37 per cent).
In common with other schools, the emphasis is increasingly on
company-specific tailored courses. Cranfield's client base now extends well
beyond the UK; it takes programmes out to the Community, Scandinavia and the
Far East. Murray even has designs on China, 'a more attractive long-term
proposition than eastern Europe, which seems to me to be a swamp.'
Back home, the public sector is tomorrow's expansion. In 1991 the School of
Management merged with the School of Policy Studies, and a range of courses
targeted at public sector managers have followed on. The most illustrious
recruit is the Bank of England - a contract agreed before last October, Mr
Norman Lamont, the UK chancellor of the exchequer, might care to note.
</TEXT>
