<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Business Schools (8): No MBAs among the masters -
LSE insists that it is really not a 'business' school at all
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LOUD fanfares greeting the recent entry of Oxford and Cambridge into the
management school firmament were notably absent from the reception given to
another of the UK's elite academic institutions, the London School of
Economics (LSE).
To be fair, so obsessed was the LSE with schemes to transplant itself to
County Hall, facing the Houses of Parliament across the Thames, that its
more fruitful projects were easy to miss.
It is now two and a half years since the LSE, Britain's leading social
science university, established an Institute of Management.
The institute is already a highly-rated undergraduate school, and it is now
about to launch both masters and doctoral programmes.
The biggest feather in its cap, however, is its status as the UK
representative in the Community of European Management Schools (CEMS).
CEMS is a consortium of eleven top European management schools. Collectively
it runs exchange schemes and aims to produce an integrated academic
curriculum for management schools across the Continent.
Other members of CEMS include Rotterdam's Erasmus University, Vienna's
Wirtschaftsuniversitat and the Ecole des Hautes Etudes Commerciales at
Paris.
The institute's director, Professor Peter Abell, insists that his charge is
not a business school.
'We are an explicitly inter-disciplinary management institute playing to a
niche - the strength of our social science faculties. We are not a
vocational training school for business studies. We do not do an MBA, nor
will we; and all the appointments to the institute are joint appointments
with other departments.' He does not mince his words as to why.
'There is some fairly clear evidence that the sort of people appointed to
business schools are not the best academics.'
By implication, 'business studies' are not thought to be much academic cop
either - a sentiment shared by a large part of the academic community in
Britain.
Abell puts it more tactfully: 'We are concerned with the management
applications of rigorous study of the main branches of social science, not
with economics, and so on, as 'add ons' to courses in 'business''.
When this coming September's intake of undergraduates arrives, the institute
will have more than a hundred first degree students. Four-fifths of last
year's recruits were from abroad; with most attaining or exceeding the
institute's 'conditional entry' standard of three A-level grades at ABB (or
the equivalent in academic standing), they are among the best qualified
students at the LSE.
The institute's masters programme in management is due to be launched next
year, with 'advanced management theory' at its core and options on subjects
such as international relations, development studies, and mathematics and
statistics to follow.
Its doctoral programme emphasises inter-disciplinary research and
quantitative methods.
Two aspects of the CEMS exercise have a direct bearing on the institute.
These are the requirement to have corporate partners, and the exchange
scheme with fellow members. The LSE's corporate partners, British Airways
and Coopers and Lybrand, have a role in curriculum development, and they
will be expected, in due course, to arrange placements for students.
All UK-resident students do an internship in another country; by the end of
their courses they are expected to be competent in three languages.
If the emphasis on economic theory and international relations marks the LSE
apart, its growth projections appear to be Xeroxed from the typical business
school of yesteryear. It wants to double in size, 'in due course'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8244 Business and Secretarial Schools.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
