<PROFILE>_AN-DD2CUADEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Business Schools (6): Cosmopolitan vigour - A look
at IMD's mission in partnership with companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMD is not as large or well known as France's Insead and the London Business
School. But among aficionados of management education the International
Institute for Management Development at Lausanne, Switzerland, is
increasingly mentioned in the same breath.
The school's 'mission' - which comes in three parts - is a useful clue to
its character: IMD wants to be as internationally-minded as possible; it
aims to teach general management skills to senior executives; it wishes to
maintain and strengthen its already close partnership with industry.
Its location in a small neutral country, Switzerland - and furthermore, in
Switzerland's minority French-speaking region - certainly helps discourage
an inward looking culture. IMD's present MBA class, 82-strong, boasts almost
30 different nationalities, and the teaching staff is similarly
cosmopolitan. For the visitor, the campus flavour is distinctively European,
with more than a dash of North American openness and vigour.
That is scarcely surprising. IMEDE - one of the two Swiss business schools
which merged to form IMD in 1989 - was itself created in 1957 by Nestle with
the support of Harvard Business School. (The other institution in the
merger, IMI-Geneva, was founded in 1946 by Alcan Aluminium.)
Today IMD is supported by 30 business 'partners', companies which typically
fill, together with 'associates'' participants, about 60 per cent of the
places on IMD courses. Partners can also benefit from tailored programmes,
such as those which concentrate on specific company problems, involving,
say, 15 to 20 employees at a time. These have represented a big growth area
in recent years, and now account for about 40 per cent of IMD's total
income.
A separate tier of financial backers comprises 80 business 'associates',
whose main contribution is to attend about 10 brainstorming sessions laid on
by the school administrators each year. 'The partners are the companies
which are really driving us,' explains Paul Adams, director of external
relations. 'We have a very close relationship with them.'
IMD's target audience is mainly those in middle and senior executive
positions seeking general management skills. In the overall business mix the
one year MBA course is relatively unimportant: it accounts for a mere 4 per
cent of IMD's income. But its significance, in terms of faculty teaching
time and the intellectual development of the school, is much greater.
IMD's flagship course at present is probably the 10 week Programme for
Executive Development (PED). Dr Peter Lorange, the school's Norwegian
president-elect says it is intended 'to make people good in a technical
sense, to make them more commercial (that is, when it comes to closing a
deal), and to improve their internal motivation.' Lorange says that longer
general management courses - with an international orientation - are doing
well at the moment; shorter ones, he adds, are proving less successful.
Though companies are often taking a commendably long view when it comes to
training - 'If you go back in history people have cut management education
budgets more than they have this time,' says Paul Adams - IMD has not been
untouched by recession. Adams points out that business schools are competing
hard for executive time, and that key managers cannot always be spared at a
time of restructuring. Overall 1992 numbers at IMD were 15 per cent down on
1990, 'though we are finding that where companies haven't hired graduates,
they are putting more money into management education.'
Adams also emphasises that the MBA course - a highly intensive 11 month
programme with an age profile of 26 to 34 - has grown in size, even if the
rate of increase of applications has slowed down. There were about 700
hopefuls for the 82 places on offer this year.
Potential areas of expansion such as Eastern Europe have been rather
disappointing. Lorange says IMD has been working with some multinationals;
teaching facilities are being developed. 'It is being done as part of our
value creation here, though, rather than sending a team over there. We do go
sometimes, but mostly to fact-find - to research.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CHZ  Switzerland, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8244 Business and Secretarial Schools.
    P8331 Job Training and Related Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
