<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Survey of Business Schools (3): Stakeholding is the buzzword
 -Andrew Adonis analyses the responses of business school students
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREEN not mean, pragmatic not Utopian.
That sums up the outlook of today's generation of business students - if a
recent survey of 700 of them from five continents and 23 countries is any
guide.
The survey was conducted by the Prince of Wales' Business Forum to coincide
with last month's annual congress of the the AISEC international student
organisation, held at Brighton in the UK. It shows the extent to which a
decade of sloganising about 'stakeholding' and 'responsibility to the
environment' have sunk in.
Asked to rank the roles of a company in order of importance, the students,
whose average age was 21, put high quality goods and services top. Skill
training came second and safeguarding the environment third (see inset).
Shareholders get short shrift, their interests prioritised (in the
management jargon) behind quality, research, workforce, even being 'a
positive force for social change.'
If that sounds a bit soppy, other questions show the greenery and social
conscience of today's students to be of anything but the 'save the whale'
variety.
On the contrary, their elders might be taken aback by the hard-headed
attitude to politics and the world beyond business. Donating funds to
not-for-profit organisations came last of the students' priorities, below
'exerting influence on government economic policy'.
Corporate reputation and success-within-respectable-bounds are what matter
most to the students surveyed, all of them at business schools or studying
business at university.
It is exhibited graphically in responses to the question: 'which perceptions
of a company will be most important for its corporate reputation?' Bottom
came: 'Good at spotting short-term opportunities for high profits'; but
second from bottom was: 'generous benefactor, contributing to charity'.
So Hanson and Rowntree are both out. 'Stakeholding' is the international
buzz-word: to the question 'will stakeholders - not just shareholders, but
employees, customers, consumers and local communities  - expect more, the
same level or less corporate responsibility in the future than today?', nine
out of ten said 'more'.
Corporate reputation was felt to be particularly important in establishing
companies overseas.
Here again, however, the element of calculating cost-benefit is barely
suppressed: although a little over half of the respondents believed
'corporate community affairs' to be an 'essential aspect of modern good
business practice', four in ten thought such matters were best left to the
company's marketing and PR departments.
Plus ca change  ..
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
BUSINESS STUDENTS' RANKING OF THE ROLES OF A COMPANY
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                         Rank
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Providing high quality goods and services                   1
Investing in the skills of its workforce                    2
Safeguarding the environment through the use of
  know-how &amp; professional skills                            3
Being at the leading edge of research and development       4
Acting as a positive force for social change                5
Making maximum profit for shareholders                      6
Exerting influence on government economic policy            7
Giving cash donations to net-for-profit organisations       8
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Prince of Wales Business Leaders Forum/AIESEC Survey
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
