<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: PM fails to calm fears of Bosnia
action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday joined Nato military leaders in saying clear
political objectives had to be set before military action was taken in
Bosnia - but did little to calm speculation that Britain would reluctantly
back air strikes if pressed by the US.
Amid continuing concerns within Whitehall and Westminster of the US
triggering precipitate action that would jeopardise western humanitarian
efforts, the prime minister's office said military operations had to be
regarded as a means to a political end.
A postponement by the US of a decision on military action until next week
will be greeted with relief in Whitehall.
Downing Street expects President Bill Clinton to consult with European
allies first.
It said the best political objective would be to implement the peace plan
which had been drawn up by United Nations' peace negotiators Lord Owen and
Mr Cyrus Vance.
Concern about US intentions and the consequences of Britain becoming
embroiled in an escalated military conflict will surface among Tory and
Labour MPs when the Commons debates Bosnia today.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, is likely to stress the importance of
humanitarian aid and the perils of various options for military action when
he opens the debate.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, Tory chairman of the all-party Commons defence
committee, said the government faced, 'a series of unattractive options. We
have to decide which is the least unattractive'.
However, the prime minister's office indicated that Britain could back the
threat of air strikes if the government believed it would achieve a
political objective.
Separately, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, said: 'There can be
military action which will help and, clearly, one will be very unwise to
rule it out completely.
'Specific kinds of military action, particularly from the air, can sometimes
eliminate sources of aggression and can deal with particular threats.'
The option of air strikes 'has to be looked at extraordinarily carefully to
make sure that it would indeed achieve the result that is being advocated',
he added.
Mr Major was responding to a warning by Sir Richard Vincent, chairman of
Nato's military committee, that western leaders had to be precise about what
they wanted to achieve in Bosnia.
Meanwhile, Labour leaders headed off an attempt by Mr Tony Benn, leftwing
Labour MP for Chesterfield, to win backing from the party's ruling national
executive committee for a policy of no military intervention.
The NEC backed overwhelmingly a call from Mr John Smith, Labour leader, for
further Serb advances to be checked by the threat of air strikes on Serb
communication and supply lines in Bosnia.
</TEXT>
