<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Pools concession may help lottery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday agreed to allow football pools companies to offer
larger jackpots in a move intended to allay some of the industry's fears
about the consequences of introducing a national lottery.
Bowing to cross-party pressure, Mr Peter Lloyd, a home office minister, said
there was 'a good case' for allowing pools companies to 'roll over' prize
money from one week to another under limited circumstances.
Mr Lloyd also told MPs the government intended to review restrictions on the
sale of lottery tickets in bingo clubs and other leisure outlets. It 'may
well' come back with proposals to amend existing rules which prohibit the
sale of tickets in betting shops, bingo clubs, casinos, and amusement
arcades, he said.
As the National Lottery Bill paving the way for the new lottery approached
its third Commons reading, Mr Lloyd said the government would bring forward
proposals to override the current prohibition on rolling over pools prize
money when the measure reached the Lords.
He said the proposals would be designed to give pools companies 'similar
freedom' to that granted to the national lottery, which he expected to roll
over its prize money once or twice a year.
Rejecting less restrictive proposals put forward by Sir Malcolm Thornton,
the Tory MP for Crosby, and supported by Labour, Mr Lloyd said these would
not create a level playing field and could result in 'spiralling jackpots'.
As part of its review of ticket sales restrictions, the government would
'give favourable consideration' to proposals submitted by Mr Peter Fry, the
Tory MP for Wellingborough, that would allow local lottery tickets to be
sold in bingo clubs.
It would be up to the organisations running the lotteries to decide where
their tickets should be sold if current restrictions were lifted, Mr Lloyd
said.
In the case of pubs, the government has said it will allow pub operators to
decide whether or not to sell lottery tickets.
Home office officials said the review would start 'within months'.
Earlier, MPs voted down by a majority of 90 (259 votes to 169) a proposal by
Mr David Alton, the Liberal Democrat MP for Liverpool Mossley Hill, that the
headquarters should be set up in an area that would suffer job losses
directly attributable to the lottery.
</TEXT>
