<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Police plead not guilty to terror
charges - Criticism of the City force
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BLUE lamp above the door of Wood Street Police station lends a Dock
Green atmosphere to the City police operational centre. The impression is
enhanced by the friendly village-bobby approach of the desk officers inside.
The desk is bereft of the toughened-glass cell-like fittings more readily
associated with the offices of the Metropolitan Police.
In character the two forces are chalk and cheese, and while the old
parochialism of the City force is not what it once was - its last four
Commissioners came from the Met - there is a scarcely veiled antipathy
towards each other.
Met officers will jokingly refer to their City counterparts as 'door
openers' because of the number of ceremonial duties demanded in the Square
Mile.
The Bishopsgate bomb has made that charge of amateurism a political issue.
And the City police are hard pressed to respond. Their normal defence is
their ability to tackle fraud, not terrorism.
The Company Fraud Department, which works closely with the Serious Fraud
Office, is the force's showcase squad.
In his foreword to the force's last annual report Mr Owen Kelly, the
commissioner, put forward unconventional though forceful argument that its
performance provided value for money.
Presenting a balance sheet for the City of London force, and excluding the
frauds in the Maxwell Group and at Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, he said the Company Fraud Department recovered or prevented
the loss of Pounds 936.1m.
A further Pounds 11m 'income' could be added from other sources such as
fixed penalty fines, giving a total of Pounds 947.1m. This compared with the
force's estimated spend of Pounds 47.4m in the 1991-92 financial year.
The report was compiled before the Baltic Exchange bomb and last weekend's
Bishopsgate blast which, using the profit/loss analogy, would have wiped the
smile off the balance sheet.
Met officers recognise City police skills at fraud investigation but few
seem willing to give any further praise. That now makes the force
vulnerable. One Metropolitan fraud squad detective said that he regarded the
City of London as a 'commercial police force'.
He said: 'In the Met it's a seven-day police operation, but the City
sometimes hasn't got cover at weekends. The City hasn't got the capacity for
dealing with terrorism.'
Arguments over the future of the City of London Police have led to renewed
debate over whether it should be amalgamated into another force  - this is
one possible area of discussion under the current Home Office review of the
organisation of forces in England and Wales.
At least twice in its history the City force has found itself the target of
amalagamation plans with other forces. On both occasions it has been
protected by its fairy godmother, the Corporation of London. The City force
said: 'Ever since we first started there has been talk of amalgamation, but
we are still here 150 years later.'
City police believe strongly that the bomb last weekend has unfairly focused
criticism on their operations, when they are in fact dependent on the
intelligence and logistical back-up provided by others.
'Before you blame us, you have to ask how it was allowed to get into our
area in the first place,' one City police source said.
This defensive position is based on the belief that an IRA operation that
was well under way when a lorry was stolen in Staffordshire on March 20
should have been detected not just by M15 but also by several other
constabularies before it reach its final parking place in Bishopsgate.
That argument has some force but it does not answer the charge that having
one extra small force, with little anti-terrorist expertise, compounds the
problems of communication of intelligence in a structure already unwieldy
because of the large number of constabularies.
If the Corporation of London wants to defend its police force it will need
more than value-for-money arguments.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
