<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lottery sale restrictions may be
eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RESTRICTIONS on the sale of lottery tickets in bingo clubs and other leisure
outlets are to be reviewed, the government said yesterday, as the National
Lottery Bill approached its third Commons reading.
Mr Peter Lloyd, home office minister, told MPs he would undertake a
'complete review' of existing rules which prohibit the sale of tickets in
betting shops, bingo clubs, casinos, and amusement arcades.
The government 'may well' come back with proposals to amend the regulations,
Mr Lloyd said. In particular it would 'give favourable consideration' to
proposals submitted by Mr Peter Fry, the Tory MP for Wellingborough, that
would allow tickets for local lotteries to be sold in bingo clubs.
It would be up to the organisations running the lotteries to decide where
their tickets should be sold if current restrictions were lifted, Mr Lloyd
said.
In the case of pubs, the government has said it will allow pub operators to
decide whether or not to sell lottery tickets.
The Home Office said the review would start 'within months'. The government
was 'sympathetic' to the idea of tickets being sold in amusement arcades but
clearing the way for them to be sold in betting shops would require primary
legislation.
Earlier, Mr Robert Key, national heritage minister, gave an assurance that
the funds distributed by the national lottery - which is planned to start
next year - would not act as a substitute for public spending.
Mr Key refused to be drawn on where the headquarters for the lottery would
be located, except to say it would be in the UK.
MPs voted down by a majority of 90 (259 votes to 169) a proposal by Mr David
Alton, the Liberal Democrat MP for Liverpool Mossley Hill, that the
headquarters should be set up in an area that would suffer job losses
directly attributable to the lottery.
Liverpool MPs have repeatedly argued that the lottery will have seriously
adverse consequences for employment in the football pools industry which is
heavily based in Merseyside.
</TEXT>
