<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Alarm at level of drug bill for NHS
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COST of drugs to the national health service was 'escalating at an
alarming rate,' Baroness Cumberlege, junior health minister, told the House
of Lords last night, Ivor Owen writes.
In defending the government's decision to consider adding new products to
the so-called selected list of drugs not available for prescription on the
NHS, she stressed that the pharmaceutical industry was being closely
consulted.
Lady Cumberlege rejected recent suggestions by Lord Jenkin of Roding (C), a
former health secretary, that the selected list system had not produced
worthwhile savings since its introduction.
She said it had produced savings of Pounds 75m in its first year of
operation but assured peers that the government was being 'more cautious' in
reaching conclusions about the addition of further categories of drugs.
'We have involved the industry more than ever before,' the minister
emphasised.
Lady Cumberlege promised to study allegations by Lord Ashley of Stoke (Lab)
that a few pharmaceutical companies were bringing the industry into
disrepute by offering inducements which resulted in some family doctors
prescribing unnecessary drugs for their patients.
Some drug trials, he said, were 'little more than drug company promotions'
and it was an outrage which should be examined by the government and the
medical profession.
</TEXT>
