<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Home Secretary Clarke says
government considering security measures request
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary, said yesterday that the government
was considering the request from the City of London for extra money to
improve security measures in the wake of the Bishopsgate bomb.
A similar request from Warrington is also being considered.
His comments came after he attended an hour-long meeting in Downing Street
with Mr John Major; Sir Francis McWilliams, the lord mayor of London; Mr
Paul Condon, the Metropolitan police commissioner; and Mr Owen Kelly, the
City of London police commissioner.
Downing Street said that the prime minister was in 'listening mode' and that
the object of the meeting was to learn the policing lessons from the events
leading up to the bomb, and its aftermath.
The security and intelligence aspects are being discussed separately between
Mr Major, Mr Clarke and Mrs Stella Rimington, the head of the security
service.
Six of the nine individuals arrested on Monday in connection with the City
bomb have been released, with the three remaining held without charge in
undisclosed police stations, Scotland Yard confirmed yesterday.
