<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Big travel groups defend position
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PALMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S THREE largest travel companies say it would not be in their
interest to use their dominant position to shut out competitors.
Executives from Thomson, Owners Abroad and Airtours have told the
Association of British Travel Agents convention in Majorca that their travel
agents will continue to sell holidays from a large number of tour operators.
Mr David Crossland, chairman of Airtours, said yesterday that Pickfords
Travel, which he purchased last year, sold the holidays of hundreds of tour
operators and would continue to do so.
He admitted, however, that the decision to buy Pickfords from the transport
group NFC was partly motivated by a desire to ensure that Airtours did not
suffer at the hands of Thomson, the biggest travel company, and its Lunn
Poly retail chain.
Airtours and Lunn Poly have had disputes in the past over pricing and the
display of brochures.
