<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Ministers clash on N Sea tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A ROW emerged yesterday between the Treasury and the Department of Trade and
Industry over proposed changes to the North Sea tax regime, which have
caused a furore in the oil industry.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, has clashed with Mr
Tim Eggar, energy minister, over the type of contracts that are eligible for
transitional relief under the petroleum revenue taxes changes proposed in
the Budget.
The new PRT regime, which would reduce the tax rate from 75 per cent to 50
per cent and abolish tax relief on exploration and appraisal work, provides
transitional help for companies which have already entered into contracts
with drilling contractors.
The industry says that obligations made to the DTI for new drilling as part
of previous oil licensing rounds should be classed as legal contracts -
automatically eligible for full tax relief - because companies are not able
to withdraw from them.
Mr Dorrell has disputed this interpretation. Mr Eggar, however, suggested
that the obligation contracts were binding.
Referring to the oil industry's drilling commitments to the DTI, Mr Eggar
added: 'There is no question of any blanket exemption.'
One leading North Sea explorer said: 'We've been getting very mixed messages
and that point certainly needs clarifying. We need to get relief or
release.'
The DTI yesterday published its 'brown book' of oil and gas statistics which
showed that the North Sea oil and gas industry contributed more than Pounds
10bn to the UK economy last year.
The industry drilled 131 exploration and appraisal wells last year. Oil
companies believe this figure could be halved if the government's proposed
changes to PRT were adopted in their present form.
Mr Eggar said the DTI had contacted companies which had made applications
for licences to drill in the North Sea as part of the 14th licensing round
but very few companies had changed their plans in the wake of the tax
changes.
The North Sea had a record 113 fields in production and the success rate for
oil exploration had improved significantly, he said.
One well in every 3.6 drilled found oil or gas, compared with a world
average of one in 20 wells. Oil production increased to 94.2m tonnes last
year from 91.3m tonnes in 1991.
Mr Eggar said forecasts for oil output suggested it would rise and reach
record levels over the next four years.
Oil discoveries reached 230m tonnes last year - taking proven and probable
reserves of oil to 2.9bn tonnes - enough to last for nearly 30 years at
present production rates.
Gas discoveries last year reached 165bn cu m.
