<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Repossessions fall adds to housing hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COURT ORDERS to repossess mortgaged houses fell 2.7 per cent in the first
quarter of the year, compared with the previous quarter. Figures released
yesterday show they were at their lowest level since the second quarter of
1990.
The figures suggest a slowly recovering housing market but analysts pointed
out that the fall appeared to be flattening out. Mr John Wriglesworth of
UBS, the stockbroker, said he still expected 70,000 repossessions this year,
compared with 69,000 last year.
The reduction in repossession orders to 26,910 from 27,656 in the final
quarter of last year was the fifth consecutive quarterly fall. The number of
orders - not all of which end in repossession - was 24 per cent lower than
the number in the first quarter of last year.
Mr Wriglesworth said the fall in repossession orders did not necessarily
indicate that fewer people were having difficulty with mortgage repayments.
Building societies had 352,000 properties more than six months in arrears at
the end of last year and the fall in orders probably indicated that more
borrowers were being allowed to go more than a year into arrears.
The number of actions initiating repossession proceedings rose to 31,371
compared with 29,583 in the last quarter of last year. They were well down
on the 42,267 in last year's first quarter, according to the Lord
Chancellor's Department.
Mr Steven Bell, chief economist at Morgan Grenfell, said that financing
house purchase through variable interest rate mortgages had contributed to
the volatility of the UK economy. Fixed-rate mortgages would damp down
swings in the mortgage interest rate, reducing the size of the boom and the
length of the slump.
He also warned that it would be hard for sterling to return to the European
Exchange Rate Mechanism unless a higher proportion of mortgages were on
fixed rates.
</TEXT>
