<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Jordan forecasts new strike wave
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC RECOVERY could be accompanied by 'a return to industrial disputes
of a combative kind' such as the bitter dispute at Timex in Dundee, Mr Bill
Jordan, the president of the AEEU engineering union, warned last night.
He told the Commons employment committee that trade union and individual
worker rights had dramatically worsened over the past 14 years.
Throughout the 13-week Timex dispute, he said, his union had fully complied
with the law but appeared to be 'not one inch nearer a settlement'.
The union has been seeking a negotiated agreement with Timex over the
reinstatement of 341 workers dismissed nearly three months ago for refusing
to accept new terms and conditions of employment.
Mr Jordan said the union agreed with Timex's aim of turning its lossmaking
plant into profit and urged the company to join the union in calling in the
conciliation service Acas to try to resolve the dispute.
Timex said in its evidence it wanted to see a toughening in the labour laws.
Mass picketing should be turned into a criminal offence, it said.
In its written submission the company said that controlling picketing by a
voluntary code of practice would 'continue to be ineffective'.
It said it had not been able to use the law against outsiders who came to
picket because it had failed to establish their identity.
Mr Peter Hall, the company's chief executive, said there had been widespread
violence during the dispute.
The company said the present labour laws had made it impossible to change
its workers' contracts of employment without going through a 12-week notice
period, which it claimed would have jeopardised its financial survival.
Mr Hall said that the company would reconsider its position on May 17, which
would be 90 days after the workers were sacked. Under existing law a company
cannot rehire workers who have lost their jobs in a mass dismissal without
facing claims of unfair dismissal by those not offered re-employment.
Mr Greville Janner, the Labour MP who chairs the select committee, appealed
to Mr Hall to settle the dispute. 'Could you not reconsider the situation
having heard what the union had to say?' he asked. Mr Hall said: 'We have
stated our position and that is that.'
</TEXT>
