<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Family Assurance status move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FAMILY ASSURANCE has become the first friendly society to apply to become a
corporate body under new legislation allowing societies to extend their
range of financial services.
Friendly societies grew out of the co-operative movement, providing
protection for workers against sickness and unemployment. Investment by
individuals in societies' tax-free savings schemes is limited to Pounds 200
a year.
Under the Friendly Societies Act 1992, designed to allow them to compete
more effectively with other providers of financial services, societies can
incorporate and offer their members and the public a variety of financial
services, including unit trusts and personal equity plans, insurance broking
and fund management services for pension funds.
Family Assurance, which has Pounds 600m funds under management, has secured
the approval of its members to become a corporate body and expects to
incorporate on July 1. It said yesterday it is to acquire Family Equity
Plan, a company limited by guarantee which manages a unit trust, to market
Peps to its 530,000 members and the public.
Liverpool Victoria, the largest friendly society with Pounds 2.7bn under
management, said it intended to incorporate after choosing the most suitable
products to market. It said: 'There is a danger that you could leap in and
then find you are in the wrong place.'
Mr Peter Gray, chief executive of Tunbridge Wells Equitable friendly
society, said the society would be putting the question of incorporation to
its members at its annual meeting in October.
</TEXT>
