<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Halifax seeks sales breakthrough by loosening its ties: An
unexpected application to the Personal Investment Authority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DESIRE of the Halifax, by far Britain's largest building society, to
join the proposed Personal Investment Authority could be a breakthrough.
It is the first building society to say it wants to join the proposed
umbrella regulatory body overseeing the sale of retail financial products,
and it cites its commercial interest in doing so.
The pay-off for the society is a chance to lobby for a change to the
polarisation rule, part of the Financial Services Act, which requires sales
agents either to be tied - selling the products of a single supplier - or to
be independent - selling the best product of a range of suppliers.
Chief executive Mr Jim Birrell said: 'The Halifax thinks of itself as a
retailer.' He added that he would like to emulate Marks and Spencer. 'If
you're a retailer, you should deal with a number of suppliers - more than
one for each mainline product.'
Apart from deposit-based products the Halifax sells no retail financial
services of its own. It is a 'tied agent' of Standard Life, one of Britain's
largest life insurers.
After a brief flirtation with independent status the Halifax opted to be
tied Life because 'the remuneration is better as a tied agent', Mr Birrell
said.
For the Halifax the tie brought in Pounds 177m in commissions, contributing
handsomely to the group's total profit of Pounds 680m for 1992. And while
Standard Life will not say how much of its business comes through the
Halifax, industry estimates are that it accounts for about a quarter of all
new policies sold.
But what if Standard Life does not offer a product which Halifax customers
want? Or if the product it does offer is not as good as others in the
market?
Mr Birrell says he has no desire to change his relationship with Standard
Life but 'there are other sectors of the financial services market where
Standard Life is not the best provider'.
He hopes membership of the new self-regulatory body will expand his range of
options. The body is to be formed by merging Lautro, the life insurance
industry regulatory body, and Fimbra, the body for independent financial
advisers, as well as the large independent financial adviser members of
Imro, the self-regulatory body for fund managers.
The life insurers have said they will not join, however, unless the retail
financial services arms of banks and building societies become members as
well.
As a tied agent Halifax does not need to be a member of a self-regulatory
body. It is regulated indirectly by Lautro, which oversees the sales
activities of Standard Life. If a Halifax-based sales agent breaks the rules
it is Standard Life which has to compensate clients.
But Mr Birrell says he wants to see the new body get off the ground. 'We
feel encouraged with the way it is shaping up and we thought it worthwhile
to say so,' he said.
Last December Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investments
Board, told the new body's formation committee that he would not approve it
as a self-regulatory body unless it significantly improved investor
protection and incorporated certain specific rules.
He has also proposed rules that could force the most marginal independent
financial advisers out of business, and limit claims on the Investors'
Compensation Scheme.
That tough stance, and signs that the new body's board is taking it
seriously, has encouraged Mr Birrell.
But he admits to his other agenda - to change the regulatory structure to
allow the Halifax and other building societies to expand the range of retail
products that they can sell.
The issue is unnerving several of Britain's largest life insurance
companies, most of which have invested heavily in developing a building
society tie. Industry sources said the Halifax had sought membership of the
new body by approaching its formation committee, only to be rebuffed by the
life insurance members.
Mr Birrell says that because the banks and building societies failed to
inject themselves sufficiently into the debate over the shape of regulation
in the years leading up to the passage of the Financial Services Act in 1987
and did not join the self-regulatory bodies thereafter, they limited their
ability to influence regulation.
'We have been disadvantaged in the initial discussions. We would like a seat
at the table and the ability to influence events,' he said. 'We are a
significant part of the life insurance industry and we haven't been able to
influence regulation.'
</TEXT>
