FT  29 APR 93 / Superdrug intensifies high street price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPERDRUG intensified its price war against rival high street retailers
yesterday by announcing an immediate 25 per cent price cut on two thirds of
all branded sun-care products sold in its 680 shops.
Prices of the remaining third of such products will be reduced by a quarter
in the next few weeks. The price cuts will remain in force through the
summer.
This latest shot in the battle for the sun-care products market - worth
Pounds 110m at retail prices - follows Boots' April 24 attempt to obtain an
injunction preventing Superdrug, a part of the Kingfisher group, from
selling its new Solait range of products.
Boots said that Superdrug's Solait was in several respects an imitation of
its own sun-care range, called Soltan. A legal hearing is likely in the next
few weeks.
The sun-care price war extends the battle between Superdrug and Boots over
fragrances. Superdrug said it achieved a 1.5 per cent market share in the
fine fragrance market - worth a total Pounds 450m at retail prices - last
year.
