FT  29 APR 93 / 20% of tankers 'below standard'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE IN FIVE of the world's tankers is below international safety standards,
the inquiry into the implications of January's Braer tanker disaster heard
yesterday.
The Chamber of Shipping, which represents UK owners and operators, told the
inquiry that it blamed cut-throat pricing, and accused governments of
lacking the resources and the will to police ship safety properly.
It said freight rates had fallen in real terms from a 1973 peak of Dollars
69.4 a tonne to less than Dollars 12 a tonne in 1991. The chamber said a
'significant number of owners' were willing to cut corners on safety because
of inadequate inspection by flag and port states, while some charterers did
not care about the state of vessels.
Inspections by oil companies had shown that '20 per cent or more of the
world's tankers do not meet existing internationally agreed standards'. The
inquiry continues.
