<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Superdrug intensifies high street price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPERDRUG intensified its price war against rival high street retailers
yesterday by announcing an immediate 25 per cent price cut on two-thirds of
all branded sun-care products sold in its 680 shops.
Prices of the remaining third of such products will be reduced by a quarter
in the next few weeks. The price cuts will remain in force through the
summer.
This latest shot in the sun-care products market battle - worth Pounds 110m
at retail prices - follows Boots' April 24 attempt to obtain an injunction
preventing Superdrug, a part of the Kingfisher group, selling its rival's
new Solait range of products.
Boots said that Superdrug's Solait was in several respects an imitation of
its own sun-care range, called Soltan. A legal hearing to decide on the
injunction is likely in the next few weeks.
Profit margins on sun-care products, like brand-name perfumes, are as high
as 50 per cent in some retailers.
The sun-care price war extends that being fought out between Superdrug and
Boots on fine fragrances. In April 1992 Superdrug made a formal complaint to
the Office of Fair Trading about alleged restrictive pricing and supplies in
the brand-name perfume market.
The OFT referred the matter to the Mergers and Monopolies Commission, which
is expected to rule by September.
Superdrug said yesterday that its experience was that consumers bought much
more perfume when it brought down the retail price - by between 15 per cent
and 50 per cent - in the approach to last Christmas.
Superdrug said it had achieved a 1.5 per cent market share in the fine
fragrance market - worth a total Pounds 450m at retail prices - last year.
It is aiming at similar target in the sun-care market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
