<DATE>930429
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / 20% of tankers 'below safety standards'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE IN FIVE of the world's tankers is below international safety standards,
the inquiry into the implications of the Braer tanker disaster heard
yesterday.
The Chamber of Shipping, which represents UK owners and operators, giving
evidence to the inquiry, blamed cut-throat pricing and accused governments
of lacking the resources and the will to police ship safety properly.
It said freight rates had fallen in real terms from a 1973 peak of Dollars
69.4 a tonne to less than Dollars 12 a tonne in 1991. The chamber said a
'significant number of owners' were willing to cut corners on safety because
of inadequate inspection by flag and port states, while some charterers did
not care about the state of vessels.
Inspections by oil companies had shown that '20 per cent or more of the
world's tankers do not meet existing internationally agreed standards. The
operators of these ships need to be driven out of business or compelled to
bring their operations up to current international standards'.
Accident rates were increasing after declining between 1975 and 1989.
Companies found it difficult to justify replacing old ships 'in the current
economic climate' even though they needed higher maintenance. The chamber
also warned of a coming shortage of officers.
Captain James Irvine, from Shell, one of the chamber witnesses, accused ship
safety regulators - including the Department of Transport - of 'lacking the
resources and determination' to keep sub-standard vessels from ports in the
UK and elsewhere.
Asked by Lord Donaldson, the inquiry chairman, if one solution to the
inspection problem might be to recruit former mariners to carry out safety
checks, Capt Irvine said this would make 'an incalculable contribution to
safety'.
The chamber said better enforcement of regulations was needed before
additional rules on routeing or ship design.
But the chamber has said it favours greater use of high-tech navigational
aids, including satellite positioning systems, and the fitting of ships with
transponders to help ship-to-ship and ship-to-shore communications.
The inquiry continues.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
