<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / World Trade News: Seoul broke Gatt rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH Korea breached fair trade rules in an anti-dumping investigation of
imports of polyacetal resins from the US and Japan, according to an
independent disputes panel of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
South Korea said it would implement the panel's recommendations to conform
with the world trade body's anti-dumping code. The code covers procedures
for identifying and levying duties on dumped imports - goods sold below cost
or below prices in the home market.
The anti-dumping investigation by the Korean trade commission led to the
imposition of duties in 1991 on US and Japanese exports of polyacetal
resins, a plastic widely used in the manufacture of audio and video tapes,
car parts and electronic components. Dumping margins were assessed at
between 20 and 108 per cent.
</TEXT>
