<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / World Trade News: Seoul breached resin trade rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH Korea breached fair trade rules in an anti-dumping investigation of
imports of polyacetal resins from the US and Japan, according to the report
of an independent disputes panel of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade.
At a meeting of Gatt's anti-dumping committee, which ended yesterday South
Korea said it would implement the panel's recommendations to conform with
the world trade body's anti-dumping code. The code covers procedures for
identifying and levying duties on dumped imports - goods sold below cost or
below prices in the home market.
The anti-dumping investigation by the Korean trade commission led to the
imposition of duties in 1991 on US and Japanese exports of polyacetal
resins, a plastic widely used in the manufacture of audio and video tapes,
car parts and electronic components. Dumping margins were assessed at
between 20 and 108 per cent.
The findings of another panel report, on US anti-dumping duties levied on
Norwegian salmon, were rejected by Norway after the panel cleared the US of
most of the alleged code violations. Washington said it was prepared to
implement the panel findings, which urged changes in US methods of
calculating dumping margins.
</TEXT>
