<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / World Trade News: Zimbabwe opens the door to investment -
Business welcome for new strategy is tinged with disappointment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY HAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HARARE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS leaders in Zimbabwe have given a cautious welcome to the package of
investment and export incentives announced by the government this week but
warn that the country has a long way to go before it will be competitive in
attracting global investment.
The government's new strategy was set out on Tuesday by Mr Bernard Chidzero,
finance minister. He liberalised dividend remittance regulations, increased
the level of export retentions from 35 to 50 per cent, widened the scope for
using blocked and surplus funds and - for the first time since exchange
controls were imposed more than 30 years ago - opened the door to foreign
portfolio investment through the Zimbabwe Stock Exchange.
There is some disappointment that the relaxation of the ceiling on dividend
remittances applies only to new investments after May 1 1993 or to companies
whose exports comprise more than a quarter of their total sales.
Mr Chidzero announced that any new foreign investment from next week would
be entitled to unrestricted remittance of dividends provided the funds are
bought in the Export Retention Market (ERS), where the premium is currently
28 per cent above the official rate of ZDollars 6.40 to the US dollar.
The related proposal to allow existing investors - either the pre-1979
companies (at present allowed to remit only 25 per cent of dividends) or
post-1979 foreign-owned concerns (currently limited to 50 per cent) - to
increase their dividend remittances in line with new investment is an
important concession, too. But many businessmen had hoped the government
would scrap these ceilings altogether and allow existing companies to remit
as much as they wished, provided the funds were purchased in the ERS or
'free' market.
The aim is to encourage existing foreign investors to reinvest in the
knowledge that they will be able to remit all profits derived from new
investment.
But it will be difficult to separate out profits generated from past and
'new' investment, and as one businessman said yesterday: 'The main
beneficiaries are going to be accountants, tax lawyers and consultants.'
The scope for using blocked and so-called 'surplus' funds, which foreign
companies have been unable to remit because of exchange control has been
widened, to allow Zimbabwe investors to purchase blocked funds and invest
them in new projects provided these export at least 75 per cent of turnover.
Also any new investment in Zimbabwe since 1979 may now be repatriated - by
way of disinvestment - provided the funds are bought in the ERS.
Foreign investors will now be allowed to buy equities on the Zimbabwe Stock
Exchange provided the funds are brought into the country through normal bank
channels. However, no single foreign investor will be allowed to purchase
more than 5 per cent of a quoted company and foreign ownership through
portfolio investment of this kind will be restricted to 25 per cent of the
total issued capital.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZWZ  Zimbabwe, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
