<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / World Trade News: China pushes to join Gatt in EC talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO DAYS of high-level talks between the European Community and China opened
yesterday, with the Chinese pressing their case for membership of the
General Agreement on Tariffs on Trade and the EC expressing concern about
Beijing's growing trade surplus.
Sir Leon Brittan, EC commissioner for external economic relations, and Mr
Hans van den Broek, commissioner for external political relations, are to
take part in the second plenary phase of talks today. The future of Hong
Kong will also be on the agenda, a Brussels official said.
The EC's dilemma is how to encourage economic reform in China as a catalyst
to political reform, while at the same time defending its markets against
what it considers unfair competition.
EC officials said yesterday that China's trade surplus with the EC had risen
to 'worrying levels', increasing from Ecu1.2bn (Pounds 940m) in 1988 to an
estimated Ecu10bn at the end of 1992. 'The deficit is still growing, while
EC exports have stagnated since 1986,' said one Brussels official.
Last month, the EC took action to protect Community bicycle-makers from
alleged 'dumping' by Chinese producers using unfairly low prices.
It announced it would set duties at 34.4 per cent of the net price before
customs clearance, following evidence that imports of racing, mountain and
other bikes had more than tripled to 2.1m - or 10 per cent of the EC market.
The Community has also sought to block toys and footwear imports.
The Chinese are anxious to avoid these kind of bilateral trade pressures
through Gatt membership.
But an EC official stressed yesterday that China's import regime fell well
short of free market principles. 'This will be of prime concern to the
Community and other contracting parties during accession negotiations to the
Gatt.'
The EC pledged to hold 'a frank dialogue' with the Chinese on human rights
as part of a progressive normalisation of political relations. This policy
follows the suspension of high-level contacts and a freeze on co-operation
in June 1989 after the Tienanmen Square massacre which lasted until October
1990.
</TEXT>
