<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / World Trade News: French call to ease stance on oilseeds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH oilseed growers were told yesterday they must accept provisionally
the production restraint negotiated by the European Commission and the US
last autumn, but rejected by France's previous Socialist government.
Mr Jean-Claude Sabin, president of the Federation des Producteurs Oleagineux
et Protagineux (FOP), said he was ready to accept the limit of 5.128m
hectares for EC oilseed cultivation, provisionally agreed by EC and US
negotiators in Washington last November. The French government had
complained that this was incompatible with Brussels' predictions that the
internal Community farm policy reform would leave oilseed growers with 5.4m
hectares to cultivate.
But Mr Sabin said acceptance of the overall deal was dependent on the US
dropping two other aspects: a minimum 10 per cent set-aside, and a 1m tonne
limit on the growing of oilseeds for industrial use. It was not acceptable
that Europe should be committed to a 10 per cent set-aside on oilseeds,
without the flexibility to alter the amount of land taken out of production
as foreseen for other crops in the EC's own farm reform.
He also insisted that the growing of oilseeds to produce motor fuels - an
increasingly promising prospect in Europe as well as in the US - would have
no effect on world agricultural markets, and therefore should not be subject
to any limit.
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur's new government has indicated that while it
would maintain France's firm resistance to the provisional EC-US accord on
subsidised exports, it is ready to be flexible on oilseeds, where the EC had
twice had its present support criticised within the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
</TEXT>
