</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Arthur Levitt, a former chairman of the American Stock Exchange, is
expected to be named by President Bill Clinton this week as the new chairman
of the Securities and Exchange Commission, the government agency which
polices the securities industry.
Mr Levitt, who is 62 and owns Roll Call, a newspaper covering Congress, will
succeed Mr Richard Breeden, a Republican appointee, who is stepping down
several months before the end of his term.
One of the most important actions facing Mr Levitt is the release by the SEC
of a long-awaited report, called Market 2000, which will present a detailed
study of the future of the US capital markets.
Mr Levitt has been favourite to get the SEC post for some months, after
edging ahead of Ms Consuela Washington, a congressional aide.
