FT  29 APR 93 / Clinton cuts rail plans down to size
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration yesterday unveiled details of its plans to
promote high-speed rail links.
They focus on upgrading existing tracks to handle faster conventional
trains, using federal money to stimulate spending on tracks by state and
local governments. More advanced technologies such as magnetic levitation,
which can propel trains at up to 300mph, have been kept out of this first
phase.
During his election campaign Mr Clinton promised the 'creation of a
high-speed rail network linking our major cities and commercial hubs'.
Budget realities, however, have forced some scaling back of these ambitions.
Trains run at moderately high speeds in a northeastern corridor from Boston
to Washington, by way of New York, where trials have now begun of a Swedish
tilting train. However, long-distance passenger rail traffic has virtually
died in most other parts of the US.
