<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Fujimori deploys psychology against rebels: Peru's
pacification policy is bearing fruit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN overnight bus ride through the wild Andean mountains west of Ayacucho,
traditional bastion of Peru's Maoist Sendero Luminoso guerrillas, is a
memorable but probably inadvisable experience. Apart from the state of the
roads, it is unnerving to be stopped and ordered to descend by a 12-year-old
vigilante brandishing a loaded Winchester.
Nine months ago no foreigner would have contemplated such a trip. The fact
that it is now possible indicates that President Alberto Fujimori's
pacification policy is bearing the fruit he has doggedly promised since his
early months in office.
In his speech to the nation on the anniversary of last April's institutional
coup - when he dissolved congress and suspended the constitution - Mr
Fujimori used recent successes in the battle against terrorism as the prime
justification for the controversial move, which provoked international
community criticism and the freezing of aid.
'The major achievement of the period has been the life sentences passed on
Abimael Guzman and Victor Polay (leaders of guerrilla groups Sendero
Luminoso and MRTA),' he said. 'Now the fiercest terrorism in the west is
being defeated, without bathing the country in blood and without
indiscriminate repression.'
The Ayacucho area, where 13 years ago Sendero declared war on the Peruvian
state, is under the command of Gen Ronaldo Rueda. He also served there in
1987.
'There's been a tremendous change,' he says. 'Although there are a few
(guerrilla) columns still bothering us, we now have Sendero on the run.'
He claims that tough army action in past years combined with today's less
repressive approach has convinced the bulk of Sendero collaborators to
switch camp and support the state instead. 'In this new scheme, the rondas
have played a decisive role,' he says.
Rondas, or peasant self-defence groups, sprang up spontaneously in the area
when remote communities decided that they must defend themselves rather than
rely on the army. Initially, their arms were pitchforks and machetes.
For the past two years, however, in areas like Ayacucho, they have been
given hunting rifles and basic military training. Armed peasants now play a
big part in controlling roads and gathering information on guerrilla
movements. They frequently take part in joint patrols alongside the regular
army.
Forty miles from Ayacucho lies Huanta, another area dominated by Sendero
until a year or so ago. Here too army and ronderos parade noisily together
on Sunday mornings to show locals who now has the upper hand. Paradoxically,
the black-shirted goose-stepping ronderos look more martial than their
military collegues, relaxed in sky-blue T-shirts.
As part of its psychological battle for the hearts and minds of the local
peasantry, the Huanta detachment recently formed a military band. It has
been swamped by invitations to perform at remote rural celebrations -
Commandante Max Salazar calls it 'my most effective counter-subversive
weapon'.
The Ayacucho batallion now spends up to 80 per cent of its time 'winning
over the population', according to Gen Rueda. So-called 'civic action'
includes road repairs, handouts of staple foodstuffs, the provision of basic
medical and dental care and the free services of an army barber.
Much the same tactics are employed in the capital's shanty-towns. Police and
army sweeps have become a regular feature of life for the poor of Lima's
'red zones'. But house-to-house searches and wholesale detentions of those
without identity documents are accepted with little or no protest.
Gen Nicolas de Bari Hermoza, head of the joint chiefs of staff, claims that,
since receiving enhanced powers, the security forces have captured 2,500
so-called terrorists. Well over a hundred have been sentenced to life prison
terms.
Under emergency decrees, the Fujimori government last year re-defined the
crime of terrorism as 'treason to the fatherland'. Those accused are tried
by special military tribunals before unidentified, hooded judges. The idea
is both to speed up Peru's ponderously slow legal system and free judges
from the threat of reprisals.
Both objectives appear to have been successful, although at the expense of
transparency and, probably, impartiality in the administration of justice.
While life imprisonment is currently the maximum sentence for convicted
terrorists, Mr Fujimori and prominent members of his ruling majority party
would like to see the death penalty reinstated. Several Peruvian jurists
have already suggested ways in which capital punishment could be applied
retroactively to certain terrorist leaders already behind bars.
Whether Mr Guzman ends his days in his specially-constructed high-security
prison or some legal pretext is found to speed his demise, he appears
finally to have lost the almost magical hold he once enjoyed over his
followers. For a former colleague at Ayacucho's San Cristobal university,
the final blow to Mr Guzman's credibility came when he was paraded in a cage
before the press.
'We couldn't believe it,' he said. 'His speech was a disaster, so
out-of-date and riddled with old-fashioned dogma. We just laughed at him -
it was then the myth collapsed.'
But, despite some encouraging signs that Peru is moving towards
pacification, the war is not yet over. Selective Sendero attacks continue in
all corners of Peru leaving over a thousand dead in the past six months.
</TEXT>
