<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Israel to allow backlong-term deportees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS and JUDY MALTZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel agreed yesterday to permit the return of 30 Palestinians expelled
before 1987 in a gesture aimed at improving the political atmosphere at the
Middle East peace talks which resumed in Washington this week, writes Roger
Matthews in Washington.
The 30, many of whom are members of Fatah, the mainstream Palestinian
organisation headed by Mr Yassir Arafat, are expected to return to the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip within the next few days. At least three
of them are former members of the executive committee of the Palestine
Liberation Organisation.
Mrs Hanan Ashrawi, spokeswoman for the Palestinian delegation, said she
hoped this was just the first instalment in allowing back many more people
and unravelling the whole policy of deportation.
Arab diplomats in Washington said the Israeli move would help bolster the
standing of the Palestinian negotiators in the occupied territories. The
Palestinian negotiating team returned to Washington this week on the
instructions of Mr Arafat following a bitter internal dispute. Resumption of
talks was delayed by nearly five months after Israel expelled 415
Palestinians, members of the radical Hamas and Islamic Jihad groups, who are
opposed to talks.
The impact of the Israeli gesture was offset yesterday by the worst day of
violence this month in the occupied territories. Israeli troops shot dead
three Palestinians, including a 12 year-old boy, and another 50 were
reported wounded.
A government reorganisation programme for Israel's banking system was
yesterday sharply criticised by the banks and their staff, writes Judy Maltz
in Jerusalem.
The programme, formulated jointly by the finance ministry and central bank,
calls for limiting bank holdings in non-banking enterprises and forcing the
large banks to sell off their banking subsidiaries.
Bank Leumi said the plan would cause serious damage to the Israeli banking
system. 'We hope the cabinet will weigh this damage against the benefits
before taking its decision,' it said.
The heads of the works committees of Israel's largest banks yesterday joined
their management in protesting over the programme and threatened to declare
a labour dispute if it was implemented. Bank managers said that while the
trend in the rest of the world is toward mergers and acquisitions, the
government will force them to sell off assets, making them less competitive.
</TEXT>
