<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Japanese industrial production rises by 0.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MODEST rise in Japanese industrial production, a sharp fall in inventories
and a marked upturn in housing starts last month, announced by the
government yesterday, confirm that the decline in the economy may have
bottomed out in the first three months of the year.
Industrial production rose 0.5 per cent in March, the second consecutive
monthly increase. Production was 2.3 per cent down on March last year, the
smallest annual decline in industrial production for 15 months.
Most significantly there are signs that manufacturing companies are finally
starting to make some headway in reducing their inventories of unsold
products.
With shipments of products rising by 1.6 per cent in March, the index which
measures the ratio of inventories to shipments fell 3.4 per cent to 106.7,
the lowest level since last September. The inventory to shipment ratio has
fallen for each of the last four months.
The upturn in production was mainly due to increased demand for cars and
consumer electronics such as camcorders. Chemical, steel and paper output
fell.
However, the modest rise in March production was well below expectations,
according to Mr Geoffrey Barker, economist at Baring Securities. Ministry of
International Trade and Industry officials warned it was too early to claim
production was set to expand again as consumer spending remains depressed.
Miti expects further declines in the next two months.
The housing market continued to rally in March with the first annual
increase for two years in construction starts for condominiums. Starts on
condominiums for sale rose by 8.6 per cent last month, compared with the
year before, while starts on houses for rent were 13.3 per cent higher.
Publicly funded rental housing starts rose 52 per cent, reflecting the surge
in public spending on construction in the government's pump priming
programme.
Total housing starts were 9.2 per cent up from last year.
Industrial investment will continue to be severely cut in the coming year,
according to a survey published by the Economic Planning Agency.
Corporate investment will fall by 11.9 per cent from the likely outturn for
this year, the steepest drop on record, the EPA said.
The forecast was based on the EPA's quarterly survey of 4,565 large
companies.
</TEXT>
