<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Serb parliament backs peace plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERBIA'S parliament yesterday endorsed an international peace plan for
Bosnia in an effort to stave off military intervention.
The belated show of support for the previously vilified plan comes a day
after tough new sanctions were imposed on Serbia and Montenegro. The new
measures were imposed after the Bosnian Serb assembly on Monday rejected a
peace plan, despite its backing by Mr Slobodan Milosevic, the president of
Serbia, Mr Dobrica Cosic, the Yugoslav president, and Mr Momir Bulatovic,
president of Montenegro.
The parliament's vote to back Mr Milosevic's appeal could signal a split in
the alliance between his ruling Socialists and the ultra-nationalist Serbian
Radicals.
Diplomats yesterday remained unconvinced by the last-minute appeal for
peace. 'There have not yet been tangible signs that they are prepared to
take the steps necessary to bring the Bosnian Serbs aboard,' said one.
Meanwhile, new clashes between Croat and Moslem forces erupted in central
Bosnia. Bosnian radio said Croat forces were launching sporadic attacks near
Jablanica and Kiseljak, just west of Sarajevo.
Bosnian Radio said Serb forces had launched an assault near Brcko, in the
north-east, while Serbian radio claimed Moslems and Croats were attacking
the area.
Bosnian Serbs warned the UN High Commissioner for Refugees that aid convoys
would not be allowed into the eastern town of Gorazde for two weeks.
According to Bosnian radio there was also heavy fighting in Bihac, the
north-western Moslem heartland.
Reuter adds: A UN Security Council team recently returned from Bosnia
proposed designating Sarajevo a UN safe area, as well as the towns of Tuzla,
Gorazde and Zepa.
This would involve the withdrawal of weapons. The first safe area declared
by the Security Council, on April 16, was Srebrenica.
</TEXT>
