<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Spanish Elections: Gonzalez takesa gamble with the peseta -
Spain's looming election is putting its currency under new pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IT WOULD be cruel to suggest that the Bank of Spain has been so stoutly
defending the peseta over the past week because there is a general election
on June 6. But it is hard to find anyone in Madrid who believes the bank's
support of the peseta since late last week has been anything but political.
The Socialist government of Mr Felipe Gonzalez is going to lose its
parliamentary majority on June 6, but it boasts so often of its commitment
to a stable peseta that a devaluation before then would be a political
disaster.
The central bank has made great efforts to stave off a probable - most
Spanish businessmen would say desirable - third devaluation in six months
until after the poll. Traders believe that, unusually, the bank has been
selling D-Marks forward for pesetas and that the official foreign exchange
reserves of about Dollars 45bn (Pounds 29.2bn) now vastly overstate the true
figure.
Minus the forward commitments, some estimates put the bank's foreign
exchange reserves below Dollars 20bn. Mr Carlos Solchaga, the finance
minister, has said any defence of the currency which drove reserves below
Dollars 30bn would be too costly.
The bank will not comment, but it is clear that Mr Gonzalez' decision to
bring the election forward by five months has changed official arithmetic.
Victory is suddenly priceless. If the bank is intervening forward, it is at
least selling its D-Marks at a profit as the peseta slides but, if the
currency is devalued, the pesetas the bank is committed to buy at current
prices in the futures markets could be expensive.
But for the government, the decision to fight off speculative attacks is
risky. A devaluation would be a very public humiliation. Mr Gonzalez added
to the turmoil of last week by conceding that the Socialists would not win
outright. He foresaw a weak government and new elections in 1994.
Spain is already in recession and will not be firmly governed for, perhaps,
more than a year. What does that make the peseta worth? Pta74 to the D-Mark
where the Bank of Spain has decided to draw its line in the sand? Or
Pta78-Pta80, where it might have a positive effect on exports?
Senior officials are approaching the weekend with some trepidation as
Saturdays are when devaluations usually take place and the Thursday and
Friday can boil with expectation. It could all begin again today, though the
currency recovered yesterday after the Bundesbank cut its repo rate. By late
afternoon the peseta was trading at between Pta73 and Pta73.30 to the D-Mark
after having fallen below Pta74 for a while on Tuesday.
So far Spain's defence has led to short-term interest rates shooting up from
about 13 per cent to 18 per cent and were rising again late yesterday from
close to 15 per cent overnight to about 16 per cent. But there is only so
much the heavily indebted Spanish can do to interest rates without ruining
the government bond market, so they have also been urgently lobbying their
friends.
Mr Gonzalez flew to Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Austrian retreat three weeks
ago, knowing that he was about to gamble on an early election and that the
peseta would suffer as a result. One effect became clear last week when the
Bundesbank led five other European central banks in a massive defence of the
peseta. Last Tuesday the Bundesbank again stood up for the Spanish, saying
it saw no reason for a devaluation.
Despite the relief yesterday, analysts believe the markets will return to
bet hard against that advice, particularly as opinion polls show Mr
Gonzalez' conservative opponents, the Partido Popular (PP), slightly ahead.
There is little doubt the PP would be happy with a devaluation. In fact, PP
supporters frequently suggest they would not be too upset if Spain left the
ERM altogether.
Mr Gonzalez, who normally has no equal as a political campaigner in Spain,
has to turn his full attention to the campaign. But even should he begin to
claw back the PP lead in the next few weeks, he is going to have to take on
the money markets as well.
</TEXT>
<XX>
