<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Bundesbank trumpets its approach to Emu: Self-confidence in
Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRIMMING with confidence in the rightness of its ways, Germany's Bundesbank
has suggested that all other European central banks should adopt its
approach to monetary policy in the interests of a smooth transition to
monetary union.
Unmoved by charges that Bundesbank policy has undermined partner countries'
efforts to escape from recession and helped promote the crisis in the
European monetary system, the bank said following its example would help
keep expansion of the European Community's money supply in line with
productivity growth, and reduce the impact of cyclical swings.
The bank said in its annual report yesterday that despite possible risks,
the lack of convincing alternatives supported the case for a pan-European
strategy steered by medium-term money supply targets.
Adoption of the Bundesbank model by the proposed European system of central
banks (ESCB) would be an especially appropriate way of achieving the
Maastricht treaties' aim of price stability, the report claimed.
At the same time the adoption of the 'Bundesbank's proven concept' would
help quickly to establish the credibility of the ESCB. Given the size of the
monetary territory involved, the report said, such policies appeared to make
even more sense for the proposed system than for a single central bank.
Running through the alternatives, the bank claimed that the scale of the
proposed European union meant a monetary system which tried to set exchange
rate targets was out of the question. Policies based on interest rates had
been proven ineffective in the past.
The suggestions, under the heading 'Thoughts on a European monetary policy
concept', followed persistent nagging from the bank's senior policy-makers
during the past year that the planned central banking system under Emu could
function effectively only if it was seen from the outset to be as
trustworthy and credible as the Bundesbank itself.
The report recommended its concept as a means of determining the interplay
between the proposed European central bank and the 'subordinate' national
institutions.
It also repeated the Bundesbank's defence of its monetary policies with a
claim that softening its stance could have 'raised the pace of inflation
throughout Europe'. As it turned out, its policy was at last beginning to
bear fruit in Germany, Mr Helmut Schlesinger, Bundesbank president, claimed
in the preface.
While the German measure of money supply, M3, grew wildly out of control for
much of last year, it now appears to have been tamed. Latest monthly figures
show expansion running below the bank's official target range. In the six
months to the end of March, a period including bouts of double-digit growth
in late 1992, M3 has expanded at an annualised rate of 5.5 per cent,
compared with 7.5 per cent in the comparable year-earlier period, the report
said.
But as it made plain in a section on Germany's public finances, there is
more to the management of inflation and monetary policy than steering money
supply between goalposts erected by the Bundesbank's technicians. In a
critique of public financing plans and the bank's first full analysis of the
recent solidarity pact - representing Bonn's efforts to cut ballooning
public deficits while fostering economic recovery in the east - the bank
finds much to worry about.
While federal spending increases this year will be kept to 3 per cent,
compared with the aim of 2.5 per cent, outgoings from regional governments
will rise by up to 5 per cent compared with an original target of 3 per
cent, while local authority spending will go up 4.5 per cent in the west and
almost 10 per cent in the east.
Despite its persistent demands that spending cuts must come before tax
increases, the bank calculates that Bonn's new budget consolidation plans
will in the medium term increase the annual burden of taxes, duties, tolls
and assorted levies by the equivalent of 2 per cent of gross national
product.
As yesterday's report said, future progress in budget consolidation will
depend largely on overall economic developments. And as it added: 'With the
proposed increases in contributions growth prospects for the German economy
have certainly not been improved.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
