<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Hoover move to cut costs could threaten Scottish plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, DAVID BUCHAN and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS, EDINBURGH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HOOVER EUROPE'S new president is re-examining controversial plans to close a
French plant and switch production to Scotland as part of a sweeping
management review intended to restore the company to profit.
Mr Gerald Kamman said yesterday painful measures would be needed to ensure
the survival of the company, which was continuing to lose heavily in the UK.
He doubted that redundancies could be avoided and said some parts of the
business might have to close.
The review risks seriously embarrassing the British government, which last
January applauded Hoover's decision to move vacuum cleaner production from
Dijon to Cambuslang, near Glasgow, as evidence of the UK's competitiveness
as a manufacturing base.
The decision enraged French authorities, which threatened to take the UK to
the European Court. If Hoover reversed the decision, it might re-inflame
Anglo-French relations.
The Scottish Office has offered Hoover Pounds 2.5m in regional aid, while
Burgundy regional council said yesterday it was ready to make an extra
financial effort to keep the Dijon plant open.
Mr Kamman said no decisions would be taken until the review was completed
next month. He emphasised that 'everything is being reviewed' and that he
believed he was not committed to carrying out the planned transfer of
production.
'These plans were put together by the previous management, and I have to
make my own judgment on whether they make sense,' he said. 'We are going to
have to do whatever is required for the viability of the company. If that
means unwinding some things, we're going to have to unwind them. I wouldn't
rule anything out.'
Mr Kamman said he had not talked to government authorities in Britain or
France. However, the Scottish Office said last night it was staying closely
in touch with Hoover. 'Further developments at Cambuslang are a matter of
considerable importance,' it said.
The AEEU recently negotiated a no-strike deal with Hoover as part of the
planned production transfer.
Mr Jimmy Airlie, Scottish member of the AEEU's executive, urged his members
to remain calm, saying he expected Hoover to honour its agreement.
The three-week review is being carried out by four executives of
Dixie-Narco, the vending machine subsidiary of Maytag, the US
domestic-appliance manufacturer that owns Hoover.
Mr Kamman headed Dixie-Narco until he was appointed president of Hoover
Europe and UK managing director, after the dismissal of his predecessor as a
result of the company's disastrous free flights sales offer.
Mr Kamman said Hoover's losses, 80 per cent of which were in Britain, were
not connected with the costs of the free flights promotion. Maytag had to
make a Dollars 30m (Pounds 18.9m) provision to cover the costs of the
campaign, leading the US company to report a Dollars 10m first-quarter loss.
Although the previous management had reorganised Hoover and sought to
improve its performance, costs were still too high and the UK company's
budget assumed it would make a loss this year, Mr Kamman said. Hoover Europe
lost Dollars 67.1m last year, after a Dollars 55m restructuring charge, on
sales of Dollars 501.9m.
Mr Kamman said the Dijon plant was close to making a manufacturing profit,
and that Cambuslang was performing reasonably well. But overheads in much of
the business had to be cut, and some product lines might have to be dropped.
In a letter to employees, Mr Kamman said there was no option to reducing
costs.
'The measures to accomplish this will have to be very strong and will
require that we run our business in ways never considered before,' the
letter stated.
Task force may be Hoover's last stand, Page 31
</TEXT>
