<HEADLINE>
FT  29 APR 93 / Wandsworth will use supply teachers to carry out tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WANDSWORTH Borough Council announced yesterday that it would bring in teams
of supply teachers to administer national curriculum tests in its four
secondary schools.
The move improves the chance that Mr John Patten, education secretary, can
salvage some meaningful results from this year's testing programme, which
faces the threat of boycotts from three teachers' unions.
It was immediately welcomed by the Department for Education as being 'in the
interests of children and of raising standards'.
Preparation for the tests is already being boycotted by the National
Association of Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers. The appeal court last
week refused Wandsworth's effort to obtain an injunction against the
boycott.
Mr Donald Naismith, the Conservative-controlled borough's director of
education, has written to the headmasters of the schools, who are legally
obliged to implement the tests if possible, offering 'support with the
supervision and marking' of the tests.
He added: 'To abandon all efforts to provide information about pupil
progress this year would be to set back the whole programme two years for
some pupils.'
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the NAS/UWT, said he would not
attempt to block Wandsworth's move.
'Effectively, they are bringing in people to help with the workload of the
tests, which is what we wanted all along,' he said. 'It is interesting to
note how extra money can suddenly be found for these purposes. It could set
a very useful precedent to assist teachers with overload in many other areas
as well.'
Opposition to the tests now includes the Professional Association of
Teachers. Mr John Andrews, PAT's general secretary, told Mr Patten that 'any
tests that go ahead now are going to be patchy and incomplete'.
Ms Ann Taylor, shadow secretary for education, said Wands-worth's action was
'incredibly confrontational'. She said she was concerned that Wandsworth
'have learned nothing . . .about the educational reasons for not going ahead
with these tests'.
Flaws in school testing, Page 25
</TEXT>
