<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Owners visit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, STEVE THOMPSON and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rumblings of dissent were being heard in the leisure sector as analysts
returned from a visit to downgrade Owners Abroad, the tour operator which
recently fought off a hostile bid from rival Airtours. Part of Owners'
defence was its bullish outlook on trading and the cost savings after its
tie-up with Thomas Cook.
While the company was said to be positive on current trading, some analysts
expressed surprise at the size of the exceptional cost items, including the
defence costs from the bid and reorganisational costs from the Thomas Cook
deal. Most downgraded their forecasts by between Pounds 3m to Pounds 6m, to
a range of Pounds 27m to Pounds 33m for 1993. Profits last year were Pounds
25m.
'If we had known the size of these extra cost figures during the bid,
Airtours would have walked it,' said one disgruntled analyst. Owners shares
shrugged off the negative talk and stayed steady at 111p. Airtours was also
unmoved, at 286p.
Stagecoach Holdings, the Scottish-based coach company, continued the long
list of highly successful stock market flotations this year. The shares,
placed at 112p, opened at 123p and were heavily traded all day, ending at
124p. Turnover reached 13m.
There were no big surprises for the market in Tarmac's results, which showed
a heavy Pounds 350m loss but a maintained dividend and no rights issue.
Dealers said the big provisions had been well flagged for many weeks and the
market was encouraged by the bullish statement accompanying the figures.
Tarmac rose 8 to 141p on high turnover of 6.5m.
Travis Perkins forged ahead 13 to 218p after maintaining the dividend in
spite of the sharp fall in profits.
Results from Sears were in line with market expectations. BZW upgraded the
stores group by Pounds 8m to Pounds 123m for 1993 and to Pounds 144m for
1994. Boots recovered from Monday's mauling over its Manoplax drug, the
shares improving 5 to 469p. Analysts said the US Food and Drug
Administration had put the drug back on its emergency agenda. It is to be
discussed on June 3.
Asda saw hefty turnover of 33m shares and the stock eased a halfpenny to 72
1/2 p. Dealers said good two-way business focused on the depth of the
supermarket group's recovery.
The Pounds 85m convertible bond from Forte is likely to lead to investors
switching out of the ordinary shares and into the higher yielding
investment. The shares slipped 2 to 194 1/2 p.
Results from Euro Disney, the French theme park operator, were badly
received and the stock fell 38 to 895p. Mr Nigel Reed at Paribas said an
equity-raising excercise was vital to the heavily indebted group, as was the
need to proceed with the second phase of the park's development. He
suggested a convertible bond issue and help from the US Walt Disney group.
Encouraging comments by Lord Alexander, chairman of National Westminster, at
the bank's annual meeting in London triggered a flurry of support for the
shares and helped the rest of the sector make good progress.
The comment from Lord Alexander that 'we are over the worst as far as UK bad
debts are concerned' saw NatWest pick up to close a net 5 higher at 473p on
relatively heavy turnover of 6.3m.
Barclays also performed well, adding 7 at 438p on 6.5m traded, while Lloyds
rose 11 to 534p. HSBC, however, eased 3 to 612p. TSB gave up 2 to 187p, but
there remained persistent talk in the market that a European predator may
still be stalking the UK bank.
Jeweller Ratners jumped 4 1/4 to 24 1/4 p on turnover of 5.8m as the market
reacted to rumoured good trading news from Zales in the US.
Leading textile group Coats Viyella held steady at 238p ahead of a buy note
from one securities house which is due out today and said to value the
shares at around 260p.
Shanks &amp; McEwan was heavily traded after a securities house bought 8.5m
shares from one institution at 183p a share and placed them with a variety
of institutional clients at 186p, a 10p discount to the market price. Smith
New Court, which specialises in large pre-arranged trades, made around
Pounds 250,000 from the deal. Shanks shed 6 to 194p.
Troubled specialty chemicals company MTM, which saw its share price collapse
last year, slipped a further halfpenny to 11 1/2 p on suggestions of a
statement today.
British Aerospace gained 6 at 322p after upbeat comments from the group's
chairman at its annual general meeting.
McKechnie, the plastics and components group, eased 3 to 423p after making a
recommended offer for USM-quoted Savage, manufacturer and distributor of
home improvement accessories, valuing it at approximately Pounds 47.2m.
Savage rose 6 to 77p.
</TEXT>
