<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Setback for CU shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, STEVE THOMPSON and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE IMPACT of last Saturday's bomb explosion continued to reverberate in the
City as Commercial Union shares fell sharply on the disclosure that the
insurer has not taken out reinsurance cover for terrorist attacks on its
pre-1993 policies.
CU said yesterday that it was lead insurer for the NatWest Tower and for the
Hongkong and Shanghai Banking building. 'CU has scored a rather spectacular
own goal,' said one leading insurance analyst.
The company is thought by insurance specialists to be liable for losses
greater than the Pounds 15m it paid out for the bomb damage caused by an IRA
attack in the City of London last year. Analysts are expected to cut current
year profits estimates for CU by between Pounds 30m and Pounds 50m, although
the latter figure is seen as a worst case figure.
On Monday, the composite sector gave ground, but more on the overall market
decline than any worries about Saturday's bomb, which dealers then believed
would have only limited impact on the insurers. Following the 1992 bomb
attack in the City, the insurance companies set up Pool Re, a mutual
reinsurance company, to manage a joint terrorism fund.
CU dropped 15 to 593p yesterday, although turnover was an unspectacular 1.4m
shares.
