<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Money Markets: Optimism on Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS a modest rise in German futures yesterday after comments from the
Bundesbank president suggested a change of attitude towards interest rates,
writes James Blitz.
In a newspaper interview, Mr Helmut Schlesinger said the Bundesbank had to
test how far it could keep cutting interest rates. He added that Germany's
economic situation had deteriorated, and that this had to be taken into
account in the setting of money market rates.
These comments, and expectations of a sharp reduction in the Bundesbank's
repo rate at its weekly money market intervention, combined to improve
conditions in both the German cash and futures markets.
The Bundesbank announced that it would be conducting a variable rate repo in
its weekly money market operations today.
The lowest accepted repo rate last week was 8.11 per cent. Many dealers
expected the rate to fall to below 8 per cent tomorrow.
Mr Adrian James, an economist at NatWest Markets in London, said: 'If it
comes below 7.90 per cent, that will be taken as a bullish signal that the
Bundesbank has moved away from gradual easing to something more aggressive.'
The June Euromark contract rose 6 basis points on the day to close at 92.67,
while the September contract climbed 13 basis points to end at 93.53. German
call money finished a touch easier at 7.57 per cent, from a previous 7.60
per cent.
The French franc market was unaffected by the move, with the June contract
closing one basis point higher at 91.99.
Conditions in the sterling market were a good deal easier. Mr Schlesinger's
comments implied that the UK might have more scope to ease policy if it
wished.
The June short sterling contract moved up six basis points to finish at
93.89. Three-month money closed  1/16 per cent lower at 6 1/16 per cent. The
overnight lending rate was seen as low as 5 per cent after a Pounds 1bn
shortage forecast by the Bank of England was easily removed by the discount
market.
However, a continuing raft of good economic data has helped to keep a lid on
expectations of a base rate cut. The Confederation of British Industry
yesterday said UK companies are enjoying their biggest increase in
confidence for 10 years.
</TEXT>
