<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Precious metals prices slipped from morning levels as gold, which had led
the rally, fell from its highs on profit-taking. GOLD was fixed at Dollars
351.40 a troy ounce in the afternoon, Dollars 1.40 lower than the morning's
eight-month high fix of Dollars 352.80. But dealers said gold's upside
target was still around Dollars 360. They also said that following Sir James
Goldsmith's large purchase of gold options, the underlying market could
expect a period of increased volatility. SILVER also fell in afternoon trade
after fixing at a ten-month high of 410.25 cents. London's robusta COFFEE
futures closed higher as the market's sharp reversal of its downward trend
continued, aided by more constructive indications on both fundamentals and
charts. The drop of more than 100,000 60-kilo bags in the latest US
certified stock figures and the good absorption of May New York arabica
delivery notices helped to fuel the upward move. Short-term charts were also
seen as reasonably constructive, with technicians looking for a close above
60.50 cents a lb for New York's July contract to reinforce bullish
formations. There has been little sign of origin selling.
Compiled from Reuters
