<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Government Bonds: Treasuries lose ground ahead of supply
onslaught
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR and JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US TREASURY prices tumbled across the board yesterday afternoon as the
market braced itself for the week's onslaught of supply following a
disappointing two-year note auction in the afternoon.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  29/32 at
102 27/32 , yielding 6.895 per cent. At the short end, the three-year note
was  5/32 lower, to yield 4.240 per cent.
Prices were weak in the morning and deteriorated further after the
afternoon's Dollars 15.25bn two-year note auction, where demand was meagre
and the yield was unexpectedly high, at 3.88 per cent.
Overall, market sentiment was negative following reports that Mr Leon
Panetta, budget director for President Bill Clinton, had become discouraged
about prospects for significant deficit reduction this year.
Economic data released in the morning put further pressure on bonds, with an
unexpected rise in the consumer confidence index for April to 67.7, from
63.2 in March.
THE UK government bond market rallied on the eve of today's Pounds 3bn
auction of 7 1/4 per cent five-year gilts which is expected to meet
reasonable demand.
The market was particularly strong at the long end, where stock typically
gained more than half a point. The 8 3/4 per cent bond due 2017, for
instance, advanced by about  5/8 to 103 1/8 .
One reason was that dealers felt the market had been oversold before the
auction. The 'when issued' price for the 7 3/4 bond gained about 3/8 ,
giving a yield of 7.05 per cent.
THE GERMAN market was buoyed in the morning by hopes of an acceleration in
interest rate cuts following a press report of comments by Mr Helmut
Schlesinger, Bundesbank president.
The bund futures contract opened higher at 95.40 and rose to 95.70. But the
message in the article was not unequivocal, and the announcement that there
would be a new bund issue next week took the wind out of the market's sails.
The futures contract ended unchanged.
Today, attention focuses on the repo rate, which is expected to come down
from 8.09 per cent to about 7.90 per cent, taking up most of last week's 25
basis point cut in the discount rate to 7.25 per cent.
THE ITALIAN market made more progress, mainly in the futures market, on the
back of the appointment of central banker Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi as prime
minister-designate.
Although lacking in political experience, he is seen as good news in terms
of support for the lira and a hard line on the budget deficit. Foreign
investors have become keener on Italian stock as the currency risk has
lessened.
A RISE in the Nikkei average index to more than 20,000 and a sharp
improvement in some economic indicators hit the Japanese government bond
market yesterday.
Alongside the rise in an index of leading indicators from 54.5 in January to
80 in February, the Economic Planning Agency fanned recovery hopes by
commenting that the bottom of the cycle had been reached.
The futures contract fell from 109.43 to 108.90, while the yield on the
benchmark 145 issue due 2002 rose to 4.28 per cent from 4.195 per cent.
Traders were also adopting cautious positions before the Golden Week
holidays.
The influence of the currency was evident in London trading. After the yen
hit a high of Y109.20 to the dollar, the futures contract recovered to
109.06. However, intervention by the US Federal Reserve - for the first time
this year on the dollar-yen front - sent both the yen and the futures
contract back the other way.
</TEXT>
