<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / UK Company News: F&amp;C forced to sell 11% stake in own trust
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Foreign &amp; Colonial Management, the manager of the UK's largest investment
trust, is to sell its 11 per cent stake in the ordinary shares of F&amp;C High
Income Investment Trust as a result of breaching Inland Revenue rules.
High Income Investment holds 30 per cent of its assets in ordinary shares
and can no longer be included in a personal equity plan, following new
Inland Revenue rules.
'Non-qualifying' unit and investment trusts have to hold investments of at
least 50 per cent in ordinary shares to qualify for a Pep subscription up to
Pounds 1,500, instead of the full Pounds 6,000 allowance.
