<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Sears up 2.8% in wake of shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEARS, the retail group, is beginning to reap the benefits of its
restructuring, Mr Liam Strong, chief executive since February last year,
said yesterday.
The group, whose retail brands include Selfridges, Wallis, Adams, Olympus
and Freemans, recorded a 2.8 per cent rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds
83.5m in the year to January 31, after exceptional costs of Pounds 31.5m,
down from Pounds 32.5m.
However, there were extraordinary charges of Pounds 112m, compared with
Pounds 11.2m, and on an FRS 3 basis Sears incurred a Pounds 47.8m loss,
against a restated Pounds 22.8m profit.
Mr Geoffrey Maitland Smith, chairman, said the group could see some signs of
improvement in trading but that economic recovery was likely to be slow.
Mr Strong said the group had largely completed the restructuring phase and
had taken encouraging steps towards putting the group's costs on a sensible
basis. Now the group had to get the shops and products in tune with what
customers wanted.
He said the balance sheet had been strengthened, with net debt cut over the
year from Pounds 153m to Pounds 47m through disposals and tighter cash
management. However, Sears aimed to step up capital expenditure from Pounds
40m last year to Pounds 70m. A property revaluation cut values by Pounds
75m.
Sales were unchanged at Pounds 1.98bn, but trading profits from continuing
businesses rose from Pounds 95.9m to Pounds 107.2m. Profits from footwear
retailing jumped from Pounds 9.3m to Pounds 23.3m as comparable store sales
grew 6 per cent, which Mr Strong put down to better product design and
sourcing, and costs were cut. The charge largely relates to footwear
business restructuring.
Speciality retailing profits rose from Pounds 25.6m to Pounds 26.9m, with
women's and children's wear strong but the Olympus sports chain incurring a
loss. Selfridges, the department store, made Pounds 16.9m, up from Pounds
16.2m.
The home shopping side suffered a drop from Pounds 29.9m to Pounds 23.2m,
although Freemans profits were up. The Dutch business acquired early last
year incurred a loss of Pounds 6.7m. Property made Pounds 22.1m, up from
Pounds 19.6m.
Earnings per share were unchanged at 4.2p, and the final dividend is 2.5p,
down from 3.83p, as forecast, to give a total of 3.5p against 5.355p.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
