<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Boarding school enrolment falls by 6% as fees rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of boarders in the UK's independent schools fell by 6 per cent
last year, the steepest decline since records began in 1982, according to
the Independent School Information Service.
This comes on top of a 10 per cent fall in the number of boarders over the
previous three years, and accelerates the decline in this sector of
independent education, according to the ISIS census, which accounts for
about 80 per cent of independent school pupils.
Term fees averaged Pounds 3,125 for boarders, a rise of 8 per cent. Overall,
independent school fees rose on average by 8.3 per cent - over three times
the rate of inflation and almost double the rate of increase in average
earnings.
The sharpest falls in numbers came at the preparatory level, with the number
of eight-year-olds falling by 16.9 per cent, and the number of nine-year-old
boarders falling by 15.1 per cent.
Mr David Woodhead, director of ISIS, said: 'We've had a long-term gradual
decline in the number of boarders in our schools and this shows the extent
to which the recession has hastened that decline.'
However, numbers at day schools, where term fees average Pounds 1,368, were
resilient, with day boys dropping by 0.5 per cent, and the number of day
girls increasing marginally, by 0.1 per cent.
This resulted in a total drop in the independent school population of 1.5
per cent - the second annual fall in succession, following nine years of
steady growth.
New spending on buildings and equipment per pupil fell by 10 per cent to
Pounds 513 as schools tried to minimise fee rises.
More than a quarter of pupils are receiving financial help, the highest
figure recorded. Schools provided scholarships or bursaries to 16.9 per cent
of pupils - more than double the rate in 1982. Take-up of the government
assisted-places scheme for pupils from low-income families rose by 3.4 per
cent.
ISIS defended the increase in fees, pointing to the cut in spending on
building and equipment, and the rise in teachers' pay in the public sector,
which it put at 9.5 per cent for 1992. Mr Woodhead said: 'Local authority
spending on education in 1992-93 is allowed by central government to rise by
7.1 per cent - more than three times the current inflation rate.'
Mr Michael Oakley, secretary of the Girls' Public Day School Trust, also
defended the fee increases.
He said: 'Our forecast is that fee increases next September will be in the
range of 4 to 5 per cent which is roughly in line with the predicted
underlying rate of inflation. Education is very labour-intensive and
anything up to 80 per cent of our costs are related to staff salaries. We've
got to keep our salary scales at least at that which is on offer in the
maintained sector.'
</TEXT>
