<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I have never talked to a lifeboat man who did not admit to being frightened
of the sea; stupid to be otherwise, you may say. But that does not prevent
them repeatedly braving the worst conditions around our coasts; among the
worst in the world. ITV begins a six-part documentary series, Lifeboat,
illustrating a year in the life of Salcombe's RNLI crew (7.00). Continuing
on The Great Picture Trail (7.30 BBC2) Neil MacGregor, director of the
National Gallery, considers Titian's 'Bacchus and Ariadne' and Mondrian's
'Composition With Grey, Red, Yellow And Blue', very suitable for printing on
tea towels. QED records how a specialist from Great Ormond Street Hospital
attempted to bring to his own patients the benefits of a Chinese herbalist
who works from a Soho basement. Six days a week Dr Luo treats the first 50
patients who write their names on a list taped to her door. Most suffer from
eczema (9.30 BBC1). It is almost embarrassing to find how little difference
the absence of Dorothy makes to the Golden Girls who are now appearing as a
trio in The Golden Palace (10.00 C4).
