<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Maxwell trustees seek claimants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRUSTEES to the Maxwell pension funds have still not traced 10 per cent
of the pensioners who may be entitled to payments, the Commons social
security committee was told yesterday.
But they have so far spent more than Pounds 4m in professional and legal
fees relating to the administration and litigation involving the pension
funds.
The details emerged during questioning from MPs, as former Maxwell employees
demonstrated outside Parliament to highlight concerns about the diminishing
amount of money available to pay their pensions.
Mr Jeremy Corbyn MP said it was 'astonishing' that so many potential
pensioners had not been traced, while pointing out that 'a great deal of
money has been paid out in fees to all the trustees'.
The trustees to the schemes said they had attempted to trace other
pensioners through a Department of Social Security service, but blamed their
difficulties on poor administration of the schemes while they were
controlled by the late Robert Maxwell.
Clay &amp; Partners, trustees to the private Maxwell companies, said it had
spent Pounds 1.3m in legal and professional fees by the end of last year.
MGN Pension Trustees, responsible for the Mirror Group pensioners, had spent
Pounds 1.7m on legal costs by January 15 this year. Law Debenture Trust,
trustees to the Maxwell Communication Pension Plan, had spent Pounds 923,000
by the end of December. All these figures excluded value added tax.
The trustees also expressed concerns that more than Pounds 75m in insurance
cover against fraud could be in jeopardy. They said the insurers were
claiming the policies were void because they had not been notified that
alleged frauds were already taking place.
At the Maxwell pensioners' rally Mr Ken Trench, chairman of the Maxwell
Pensioners' Action Group, criticised the government for its short-term
approach, which he said was using emergency funding to pay current pensions
and took no account of future hardship payments.
Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP for Birkenhead who chairs the social security
committee, told the pensioners rally that he believed there was 'light at
the end of the tunnel'.
He said the trustees now showed 'guarded optimism' that within a five-year
period money would come in from various sources 'to pay the vast majority'
of pensioners and those still to retire their due.
</TEXT>
