<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Little appetite for diet of
military involvement - Philip Stephens considers the issues facing
Conservatives over the civil war in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   by PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LADY THATCHER caught the moment. But it was only a moment. As the government
contemplates acquiescence in US-led military action against Serbia it is
being warned quietly but firmly by its supporters at Westminster against
dragging Britain into the bloody civil war in Bosnia.
The outrage and frustration at Serbian atrocities against the Bosnian
Moslems which Lady Thatcher articulated 10 days ago have not disappeared.
They will be rekindled by the latest offensive against the Moslem enclave of
Bihac.
If Serbia reacts to the tightening of sanctions by seizing the besieged town
of Srebrenica the former prime minister may be able to claim another moment.
But as Conservative MPs have contemplated more carefully the implications of
western air strikes or the lifting of the international arms embargo, their
rage has been tempered by the harsher military and political realities.
The savagery of the Croatian latest attacks on Moslem villages has reminded
them that it is a three-sided civil war with no clear front lines to defend,
no ready-made safe havens to be protected. No-one believes the Vance-Owen
peace plan could be imposed by force. Soundings in their constituencies have
persuaded MPs that the nation's anger at the atrocities shown nightly on
television news has yet to translate into a willingness to see British
soldiers fight and die in an attempt to impose peace.
Nor is the Labour party speaking with one voice. Mr John Smith's public
backing for limited air attacks on Serbian supply lines in Bosnia has won
far-from-universal support among his frontbench colleagues. No-one is
questioning it publicly but some are dismayed, others are furious.
If Mr John Major judges, as is likely, that the transatlantic alliance
demands that he stands beside President Bill Clinton then the odds are that
his party will rally round. There is a deep-seated tradition in the
Conservative party that the government must be supported during
international crises and the Nato alliance is guarded preciously.
But, with the exception of a handful who have called consistently for
military intervention, it is difficult to detect any enthusiasm for such a
policy on the Tory back benches. Instead there is a determination to ensure
the government draws a firm line beyond which it will never step.
Mr Michael Jopling, a former chief whip, sums up the mood: 'Everybody is
frustrated, everybody is horrified. The question, though, is what is best'.
The lesson from past conflicts is that air strikes will achieve little. Mr
Jopling's question is rhetorical: 'Is the advantage of bombing cancelled out
by a halt to humanitarian aid?'
His scepticism is echoed by Mr Tim Renton, another respected figure on the
back benches: 'We have to accept this is a civil war . . The idea that we
can bomb the Serbs into better behaviour is totally unrealistic'.
In private conversations other prominent backbenchers are more forthright.
It would be 'lunacy' says one, for Britain to risk being drawn into a
conflict: '(Lady) Thatcher said what I would have loved to. But I don't
believe a word of it.'
Reluctant acceptance that limited air strikes may be inevitable is coupled
with an insistence that British ground forces must not become involved in
the fighting. If there is the slightest risk that bombing will make them a
target for Serbian attacks, the existing forces must be withdrawn
immediately. There can be no question of large-scale reinforcement.
For Mr Douglas Hurd, the mood is at once helpful and dangerous. The foreign
secretary is less than popular among those seeking a military solution. Lady
Thatcher described his argument against lifting the arms embargo - it would
create a level killing field - as disgraceful.
The once-young fogeys on the fringes of the Tory right who believe that
western force is all that is needed to re-establish order in the Balkans see
Mr Hurd as the symbol of establishment appeasement.
But his strong opposition to removal of the arms embargo - and his
commonsense observation that it could not be lifted only for the Moslems -
is widely shared among Conservative and Labour MPs.
The general view is it might salve temporarily European consciences but that
it would increase greatly the level of suffering. The humanitarian aid
effort would not survive the inevitable escalation in the conflict.
The foreign secretary's careful refusal over several months to discount the
possibility of the west being pushed into military action has left him in
front of, rather than behind, the opinion in his party. His weekend decision
to commit British forces to the defence of the Canadian peace-keeping troops
in Srebrenica did the same. Most of his cabinet colleagues - Mr Malcolm
Rifkind the most important - are also more cautious.
Mr Hurd is far from enthusiastic about air strikes. He has stressed
repeatedly his belief that in the end there will be no alternative to a
political agreement. He wants more time for the tougher sanctions regime to
take effect. Guaranteeing order in the former Yugoslavia, as he puts it,
would impose huge risks over an indefinite period. The risks could not be
justified to the people of Britain. If he acquiesces in a decision by
Washington to press ahead regardless it will be with great reluctance. The
Conservative party will be more reluctant still.
</TEXT>
