<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Councils to change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNTY councillors elected on May 6 will find the councils they run changing
rapidly with the growth in compulsory competitive tendering, John Willman
writes.
Since 1988, services such as grounds maintenance and catering services have
been subject to tendering. By the time of the next elections, white-collar
services in information technology, finance, personnel, construction and
corporate services will also have been put out to tender.
The majority of contracts have been won by council workforces. But
contracting-out forces councils to put operations on a more businesslike
footing and make a 5 per cent rate of return on capital.
Labour remains opposed to tendering in principle, although it appears to be
relaxing its opposition following last year's election defeat. Labour
councils have found the threat of contracting-out helpful in persuading
employees to increase the effic-iency and quality of services.
Some councils, including Berkshire, have decided to go further than required
in contracting out all but core activities.
None has yet reached the state envisioned by the late Lord Ridley who
foresaw local authorities meeting once a year to hand out contracts for the
whole range of council services. But the 'enabling council', which sees its
role as buying services and ensuring high standards, is here to stay.
</TEXT>
