<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: MPs warn on risks of rail
privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMMONS transport committee yesterday labelled the government's rail
privatisation plans 'novel and untested' and warned that they could go badly
wrong.
The committee's final report on the government's proposals said investment
was more important to the railways' future than whether they were
privatised.
But MPs stopped short of condemning the privatisation plans outright, saying
they might hold the potential for an improved system.
'Rail users will be the final judge of whether the legislation currently
before the House succeeds in maintaining the opportunities for private
profit,' they concluded.
A hostile report had been expected because the transport committee is
chaired by anti-privatisation Conservative MP Mr Robert Adley. But the
strongest criticisms appear to have been toned down to secure the backing of
other Conservative members.
The report broadly approves the government's plans for rail freight
privatisation but expresses reservations about the idea of open access to
the tracks for competing passenger-train operators and the separation of
ownership of the tracks and trains. It says budgetary constraints could lead
to line closures.
The committee says no comparable railway in the world has adopted the form
of privatisation proposed for the UK. 'This does not of itself mean that it
cannot succeed,' the report says. 'What it does mean is that because of the
lack of previous experience to draw upon, the risk that something could go
badly wrong is that much higher.'
Mr Roger Freeman, public transport minister, said there was no reason why
any services should close as a result of privatisation. 'The only services
that will close, and I am sure that will happen, are those that close
because of lack of passenger demand. But I don't want to go down in history
as the junior minister who was the grandson of Beeching.'
Mr Freeman said many of the other criticisms had been overtaken by events
and he undertook to respond to the others before the Railways Bill reached
report stage.
Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, said the MPs' report showed
that the nation would end up with 'a lawyers' paradise and a passengers'
hell'.
The government plans to press ahead with a bill to privatise London's buses
as part of a strategy to put consumer choice and deregulation at the heart
of its next legislative programme.
Whitehall officials said yesterday that Mr MacGregor had secured a place for
the bill in the programme for the Queen's Speech which will be endorsed by
the cabinet tomorrow.
The Future of the Railways in the Light of the Government's White Paper
Proposals. Transport Committee, Second Report. HoC Paper 246-1. HMSO Pounds
22.80.
</TEXT>
