<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Civil servants call for code of
ethics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNION representing Whitehall's top civil servants yesterday called for
an independent commission of inquiry to examine the relationship between the
Civil Service and ministers.
The First Division Association told the cross-party Commons Treasury and
Civil Service committee the commission should draft a code of ethics to
strengthen the political neutrality of the ser-vice.
Ms Elizabeth Symons, FDA general secretary, said public confidence in the
Civil Service had been shaken by events such as the sale of arms to Iraq
revealed in the Matrix-Churchill trial, sterling's departure from the
European exchange rate mechanism and the pit closure fiasco.
A code would set out the rules governing relationships between civil
servants and ministers, Ms Symons said.
The conventions under which the Civil Service had operated since the last
century needed updating following a decade of radical managerial reform in
the Civil Service.
An independent ombudsman was needed, she said, to whom civil servants could
appeal when they believed they had been asked to work outside normal Civil
Service rules.
Ms Symons said the union regularly received complaints from members about
things they had been asked to do. In most cases, members were unwilling to
use the current appeal procedure which requires them to raise complaints
with their managers.
MPs also heard a call to introduce renewable, fixed-term contracts for top
policymaking civil servants from Mr Graham Mather, president of the European
Policy Forum, a free-market think tank.
</TEXT>
