<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Major and Smith clash on testing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIME MINISTER John Major yesterday rejected Labour demands to suspend this
year's school tests, while appearing to acknowledge that some of the
concerns voiced by 'ordinary teachers' were justified, David Owen writes.
Challenged repeatedly by Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, Mr Major
emphasised the importance ministers attached to the principle of testing and
denounced teachers who thought it appropriate to take industrial action at
the expense of this year's exams for seven and 14-year-olds.
But he said the government was 'considering and responding to' the concerns
of teachers who simply wanted less bureaucracy.
Mr Smith urged the government to 'for once listen' to the considered
judgement of the whole teaching profession and to suspend the tests.
He called on Mr John Patten, the education secretary, to recognise he had
lost the argument. He said: 'This increasingly bitter dispute is not about
the principle of sensible testing but about the dogmatic insistence of an
arrogant education secretary that his view must prevail against that of
governors, teachers and parents.'
</TEXT>
