<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Wellcome transfers Dollars 400m to US trust
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WELLCOME Trust, the largest UK medical charity, is to transfer Dollars
400m (Pounds 260m) to its smaller sister organisation in the US over the
next five years, Clive Cookson writes.
The gift to the Burroughs Wellcome Fund may disappoint some British
researchers who had counted on receiving all the money the trust received
after last July's sale of its majority stake in Wellcome, the drugs company.
Mr Roger Gibbs, chairman of the Wellcome Trust, said it was the governors'
prime duty 'to interpret the will and wishes of the founder Sir Henry
Wellcome', who was born and educated in the US. 'We believe it would be Sir
Henry's fervent wish that the trust should make a significant contribution
to medical research in the US.'
Dr Bridget Ogilvie, director, said the gift would amount to about 5 per cent
of the trust's total asset base - Pounds 5.4bn at current stock prices.
Because it was a transfer of capital and would not be paid out of current
income, the gift would not affect immediately the grants to UK researchers,
which have been rising rapidly for several years and will be about Pounds
140m this year.
Dr Ogilvie said there was also a message to politicians in the UK: 'It's not
our duty to save British science - that's the government's duty.'
The total spending of the Wellcome Trust and smaller medical charities has
overtaken that of the state-funded Medical Research Council, which spends
about Pounds 200m a year on grants.
The gift will transform the fortunes of the Burroughs Wellcome Fund - which
has a capital base of only Dollars 35m, disbursing Dollars 4m a year in
grants - into one of the top 50 non-profit foundations in the US over the
next five years.
The fund's directors have not yet decided how to spend the money, but it is
expected to concentrate on giving grants to promising young researchers and
to research into neglected areas such as parasitology.
</TEXT>
