<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / PM plea on terror cover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday urged cross-party support for the government's aid
scheme for insurance against terrorist attacks as the City's security came
under growing scrutiny in the wake of Saturday's bombing.
Mr Major was speaking ahead of a meeting today with Sir Francis McWilliams,
lord mayor of London, to discuss improvements to security measures.
The lord mayor is expected to raise the question of whether policing levels
in the City should be raised, although he will also point out that, like
other local authorities, the Corporation of London is limited by
rate-capping legislation.
Large banks and other companies in the City are expected to increase
pressure for a review of security at a meeting with Sir Francis tomorrow
evening. The meeting, due to be attended by the heads of more than 20 of the
largest banks in the City, was called before the bomb attack to discuss the
financial district's transport problems.
The prime minister, responding to pressure for a review of security
following the attack, refused to rule out the introduction of an identity
card system. But he added: 'I have to say that it is not immediately on our
agenda.'
Mr Major said legislation on the terrorist insurance scheme would be debated
by MPs 'as soon as possible'.
Government business managers expect the terrorist insurance legislation to
become law well before MPs rise for the summer recess. Labour last night
appeared unlikely to oppose the bill.
In the Commons, Mr Major said cover under the scheme, announced last year by
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, had been provided since
January 1. He reiterated that the government would honour its commitments
under the scheme.
Mr Major said: 'The government scheme is one of reinsurance for the
industry. Those who suffered damage will need to make their claims to their
insurers in the usual way.'
Lord Alexander, chairman of National Westminster Bank, told the bank's
annual general meeting that NatWest had achieved 'business as usual'.
