<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Government pledge on market testing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is determined to push ahead with its market-testing programme
in the public sector, in spite of doubts about the legal framework for
transferring employment protection undertakings to private industry, Mr
William Waldegrave, chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster, told the IoD
conference.
He announced a fresh initiative to publicise the programme, involving
regular publication from the summer of a market-testing contracts bulletin.
This will announce the future programmes of all government departments, and
all individual contracts as they are put out to tender.
'This bulletin will provide full information to companies who wish to
compete in our market-testing programme, and will be of particular
importance to smaller companies,' Mr Waldegrave said.
'The programme is moving forward, contracts are being let in-house and
out-house, and will result in high standards in the service delivered and
substantial savings to the taxpayer in the cost of delivery . . . It is a
rolling programme which will continue to build on achievements year by
year.'
He said if the government did not win efficiency gains in the public sector
comparable with those in private industry then the government share of gross
domestic product would increase inexorably, whether or not new public sector
commitments were taken on.
In any modern democracy, Mr Waldegrave said, the government was always going
to direct about 40 per cent of the national wealth because of spending on
defence, welfare, education, science and health. What could not be shirked
was responsibility for how that 40 per cent was managed.
</TEXT>
