<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Wales 'expects to accelerate away from recession'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS CONFIDENCE in Wales, encouraged by rising new orders, has shown the
strongest increase since the CBI Welsh industrial trends survey started in
1978.
The CBI says the recession in Wales may be over. 'The indications are that
Wales may in fact be somewhat ahead of the UK as a whole.'
The positive balance of 35 per cent of Welsh companies which are more
optimistic this quarter compares with 22 per cent in the previous quarter.
The CBI says that much of the improvement in orders, has come from exports
but there has also been a marked increase in domestic orders. The positive
balance of 30 per cent of companies reporting overall higher orders is the
highest for five years.
There was a positive balance of 26 per cent of Welsh companies reporting
higher output, the largest increase since July 1988 and an improvement not
seen in the UK as a whole.
There is also more optimism on employment. A small positive balance of 6 per
cent of Welsh manufacturers reported that employment levels had increased
over the last quarter. Greater increases in employment are expected over the
next four months, although the CBI gives a warning that these may not
materialise because of the need to stay competitive.
The CBI says a shortage of internal finance is now the most significant
factor limiting capital expenditure authorisations over the next 12 months
and 48 per cent of Welsh companies mentioned this.
Sir Peter Phillips, chairman of the CBI Wales industrial trends panel, said
the survey suggested 'Wales manufacturing has at last turned the corner and
expects to accelerate away from recession'.
</TEXT>
