<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 93 / Scottish industry raises confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH INDUSTRY has seen the biggest improvement in confidence for five
years, according to the CBI's industrial trends survey, accompanied by an
improvement in export orders and export deliveries.
The survey of 134 companies showed a balance of 12 per cent more optimistic
than they were four months ago.
This compares with the 31 per cent balance for the UK as a whole and
suggests that Scottish manufacturers are more cautious than their
counterparts in England and Wales.
Scottish manufacturers also reported a further fall in orders and output in
the first four months of 1993, against expectations of a small rise,
although the rate of deline was the smallest since 1990.
Mr John Ward, vice-chairman of the CBI in Scotland, said that in spite of
the improved export performance, future export prospects were tempered by
the weakening of markets in continental Europe, especially in Germany.
Europe was the traditional destination of 60 per cent of Scottish exports.
He said there were signs of a marked slowdown in unit cost increases with
better prospects for more competitive prices, especially in export markets.
Scottish manufacturers are continuing to reduce planned investment for the
year ahead with a higher proportion of Scottish businesses than in the UK as
a whole saying they will cut investment. Labour shedding has continued at a
considerable rate in the past four months.
</TEXT>
<XX>
